window.MM['oph_p2_neurooph']=[
  {q:"A 55-year-old diabetic presents with complete ptosis, eye deviated down and out, and a fixed dilated pupil. What is the most likely cause?",o:["Posterior communicating artery aneurysm","Microvascular ischaemic third nerve palsy","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Weber syndrome","Horner syndrome"],a:0,e:"Pupil involvement in third nerve palsy indicates surgical compressive cause. Posterior communicating artery aneurysm compresses the parasympathetic pupillomotor fibres located peripherally on the nerve.<br><br>Urgent CT angiography or MR angiography is mandatory. Neurosurgical clipping or endovascular coiling treats the aneurysm. Horner syndrome with ptosis, miosis and anhidrosis localising the lesion is a recurring exam theme.<br><br>Microvascular ischaemia (B) spares the pupil. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (C) causes multiple cranial nerve palsies. Weber syndrome (D) is a midbrain fascicular lesion. Horner syndrome (E) causes partial ptosis with miosis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old hypertensive diabetic presents with complete ptosis and complete ophthalmoplegia but a normal reactive pupil. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Posterior communicating artery aneurysm","Microvascular ischaemic third nerve palsy","Uncal herniation","Cavernous sinus meningioma","Myasthenia gravis"],a:1,e:"Pupil-sparing complete third nerve palsy in a diabetic hypertensive strongly indicates microvascular ischaemia. The central nerve fibres are selectively ischaemic while peripheral pupillomotor fibres are spared.<br><br>Management is observation and vascular risk factor control. Complete recovery expected within three months. Optic nerve sheath meningioma with tram-track calcification is a classic imaging discriminator.<br><br>PComA aneurysm (A) causes pupil involvement. Uncal herniation (C) involves pupil dilation. Cavernous sinus meningioma (D) causes multiple cranial nerve involvement. Myasthenia gravis (E) causes fatigable ptosis without ophthalmoplegia.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with third nerve palsy develops aberrant regeneration showing lid elevation on downgaze. What does this phenomenon indicate?",o:["Microvascular ischaemic aetiology","Spontaneous recovery without underlying cause","Compressive lesion causing misdirected nerve regeneration","Myasthenia gravis mimicking third nerve palsy","Nuclear"],a:2,e:"Aberrant regeneration of the third nerve indicates a compressive cause such as aneurysm or tumour. Ischaemic third nerve palsy never produces aberrant regeneration. This is a critical diagnostic rule.<br><br>Synkinetic movements include lid elevation on adduction or downgaze and adduction on attempted upgaze representing misdirected axonal sprouting. A painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy raising aneurysm suspicion is a high-stakes emergency.<br><br>Microvascular ischaemia (A) never causes aberrant regeneration. Spontaneous recovery (B) is incorrect as aberrant regeneration indicates compressive pathology. Myasthenia gravis (D) causes fatigable ptosis. Nuclear lesion (E) would not produce peripheral misdirected regeneration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old presents with right-sided third nerve palsy and contralateral hemiparesis. MRI shows a midbrain lesion. Which syndrome is this?",o:["Benedikt syndrome","Claude syndrome","Nothnagel syndrome","Weber syndrome","Parinaud syndrome"],a:3,e:"Weber syndrome results from a ventral midbrain lesion involving the third nerve fascicle and corticospinal tract causing ipsilateral third nerve palsy with contralateral hemiparesis. Stroke is the most common cause.<br><br>The fascicle is damaged before exiting the midbrain causing nuclear ophthalmoplegia combined with long tract signs. A painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy raising aneurysm suspicion is a high-stakes emergency.<br><br>Benedikt syndrome (A) involves the red nucleus causing contralateral tremor. Claude syndrome (B) involves superior cerebellar peduncle. Nothnagel syndrome (C) involves the superior colliculus. Parinaud syndrome (E) is a dorsal midbrain syndrome.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old presents with ipsilateral third nerve palsy and contralateral cerebellar ataxia and tremor. MRI shows a midbrain tegmental lesion. Which syndrome is this?",o:["Weber syndrome","Claude syndrome","Nothnagel syndrome","Parinaud syndrome","Benedikt syndrome"],a:4,e:"Benedikt syndrome results from a tegmental midbrain lesion involving the third nerve fascicle and red nucleus causing ipsilateral third nerve palsy with contralateral cerebellar tremor and ataxia.<br><br>Stroke and tumour are the most common causes. MRI brain confirms the tegmental midbrain lesion location. A painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy raising aneurysm suspicion is a high-stakes emergency.<br><br>Weber syndrome (A) causes contralateral hemiparesis not tremor. Claude syndrome (B) involves the superior cerebellar peduncle differently. Nothnagel syndrome (C) involves the superior colliculus. Parinaud syndrome (D) is a dorsal midbrain syndrome causing upgaze palsy.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old presents with bilateral ptosis, bilateral ophthalmoplegia sparing the pupil, and proximal muscle weakness. Anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies are positive. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Myasthenia gravis","Chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia","Kearns-Sayre syndrome","Third nerve palsy","Cavernous sinus thrombosis"],a:0,e:"Myasthenia gravis causes fatigable bilateral ptosis and ophthalmoplegia always sparing the pupil. Positive anti-AChR antibodies confirm the diagnosis. The ice test temporarily improves ptosis.<br><br>Pyridostigmine is first-line treatment. Thymectomy is indicated for thymoma-associated cases. Immunosuppression with steroids and azathioprine treats refractory disease. A painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy raising aneurysm suspicion is a high-stakes emergency.<br><br>CPEO (B) is mitochondrial without fatigability. Kearns-Sayre (C) includes cardiac conduction defects and retinal pigmentary changes. Third nerve palsy (D) is unilateral with specific muscle involvement. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (E) causes multiple cranial nerve palsies.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with vertical diplopia worse on downgaze and reading. He tilts his head to the left shoulder. The right eye is hypertropic. Which nerve is affected?",o:["Left trochlear nerve","Left abducens nerve","Right abducens nerve","Right trochlear nerve","Right oculomotor nerve"],a:3,e:"Right trochlear nerve palsy causes right superior oblique weakness. The right eye cannot depress in adduction causing vertical diplopia worse on downgaze and reading. Head tilt to the left compensates.<br><br>The Bielschowsky head tilt test to the right increases hypertropia confirming the diagnosis.<br><br>Left abducens (B) causes horizontal diplopia. Right abducens (C) causes horizontal diplopia. Left trochlear (A) would cause left eye hypertropia with head tilt to the right. Right oculomotor (E) causes complete ophthalmoplegia with ptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The Bielschowsky head tilt test is used to diagnose palsy of which cranial nerve?",o:["Third nerve","Sixth nerve","Fourth nerve","Seventh nerve","Fifth"],a:2,e:"The Bielschowsky head tilt test specifically diagnoses fourth nerve palsy. Tilting the head toward the affected side increases the hypertropia confirming superior oblique weakness.<br><br>The test exploits the torsional function of the superior oblique and superior rectus muscles. The hypertropia worsens because the intorting muscle is paralysed.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) causes ptosis and complete ophthalmoplegia. Sixth nerve palsy (B) is diagnosed by failure of abduction. Seventh nerve (D) causes facial palsy. Fifth nerve (E) causes facial sensory loss and jaw weakness.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old presents with bilateral fourth nerve palsy following a road traffic accident with head trauma. Which anatomical feature explains bilateral trochlear nerve palsy from head trauma?",o:["Both trochlear nerves exit ventrally from the brainstem","Both abducens nerves are close together in the pons","Both trochlear nerves decussate and exit dorsally from the midbrain","Trochlear nerves pass through the cavernous sinus bilaterally","Trochlear nerves are the"],a:2,e:"The trochlear nerves decussate in the anterior medullary velum and exit dorsally from the midbrain. A single dorsal midbrain contusion at the anterior medullary velum can damage both nerves simultaneously.<br><br>This is the only cranial motor nerve exiting dorsally making it uniquely vulnerable to dorsal midbrain trauma. This is a recurring high-yield neuro-ophthalmology localisation worth recognising at a glance.<br><br>Ventral exit (A) describes the oculomotor nerve. Abducens proximity in pons (B) is anatomically unrelated. Cavernous sinus (D) is where both fourth nerves travel but not the cause of bilateral palsy after trauma. Trochlear nerve length (E) is a fact not explaining bilateral palsy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old presents with horizontal diplopia worse on left gaze. The left eye fails to abduct. MRI shows a left pontine lesion. Which cranial nerve is involved?",o:["Third nerve left","Fourth nerve left","Fifth nerve left","Sixth nerve left","Seventh nerve left"],a:3,e:"Left sixth nerve palsy causes failure of left eye abduction producing horizontal diplopia maximal on left gaze. A pontine lesion at the sixth nerve nucleus or fascicle is the likely cause.<br><br>Sixth nerve palsy is a false localising sign in raised intracranial pressure as the long intracranial course makes it susceptible to traction. A painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy raising aneurysm suspicion is a high-stakes emergency.<br><br>Third nerve (A) causes adduction and elevation failure. Fourth nerve (B) causes vertical diplopia. Fifth nerve (C) causes facial sensory loss. Seventh nerve (E) causes facial palsy which may coexist with sixth nerve palsy in Foville syndrome.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old presents with sixth nerve palsy, ipsilateral facial nerve palsy, and contralateral hemiplegia. Where is the lesion?",o:["Cavernous sinus","Cerebellopontine angle","Orbital apex","Clivus","Pontine tegmentum"],a:4,e:"Foville syndrome results from a pontine tegmental lesion causing ipsilateral sixth and seventh nerve palsy with contralateral hemiplegia. Stroke is the most common cause.<br><br>The sixth nucleus and seventh nerve fascicles are anatomically adjacent in the pons explaining their combined involvement in a single pontine lesion. This is a recurring high-yield neuro-ophthalmology localisation worth recognising at a glance.<br><br>Cavernous sinus (A) causes multiple cranial nerve palsies without hemiplegia. Cerebellopontine angle (B) causes fifth, seventh, and eighth nerve involvement. Orbital apex (C) causes optic nerve and third, fourth, sixth nerve involvement. Clivus (D) compresses sixth nerve without seventh nerve palsy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old presents with sixth nerve palsy, fifth nerve sensory loss, and Horner syndrome on the same side. Where is the lesion?",o:["Cavernous sinus","Orbital apex","Pontine tegmentum","Petrous apex","Superior orbital fissure"],a:0,e:"The cavernous sinus contains the third, fourth, sixth cranial nerves and the ophthalmic and maxillary divisions of the fifth nerve plus the sympathetic fibres around the internal carotid artery. A cavernous sinus lesion produces this combination.<br><br>Causes include cavernous sinus thrombosis, meningioma, and carotid-cavernous fistula. Pulsatile proptosis with bruit and corkscrew vessels pointing to a carotid-cavernous fistula is a classic triad.<br><br>Orbital apex (B) spares the maxillary fifth nerve division. Pontine tegmentum (C) causes sixth and seventh nerve involvement. Petrous apex (D) causes Gradenigo syndrome with fifth and sixth nerve involvement. Superior orbital fissure (E) spares the maxillary fifth nerve division.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with painful ophthalmoplegia involving the third, fourth, and sixth cranial nerves with fifth nerve sensory loss. MRI shows granulomatous inflammation at the cavernous sinus. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Tolosa-Hunt syndrome","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Carotid-cavernous fistula","Sphenoid wing meningioma","Orbital"],a:0,e:"Tolosa-Hunt syndrome is a painful ophthalmoplegia caused by idiopathic granulomatous inflammation of the cavernous sinus or superior orbital fissure. It responds dramatically to systemic corticosteroids.<br><br>Diagnosis requires exclusion of other cavernous sinus pathology by MRI. Recurrence is recognised and may require prolonged steroid therapy. Tolosa-Hunt painful ophthalmoplegia with cavernous sinus enhancement is a recurring discriminator.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (B) causes fever and proptosis. Carotid-cavernous fistula (C) causes pulsatile proptosis and bruit. Sphenoid wing meningioma (D) causes gradual onset without dramatic steroid response. Orbital pseudotumour (E) causes proptosis and lid swelling.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old presents with right-sided sixth nerve palsy, right-sided facial pain, and right-sided deafness. Where is the lesion?",o:["Cavernous sinus","Pontine tegmentum","Cerebellopontine angle","Petrous apex","Orbital apex"],a:3,e:"Gradenigo syndrome results from petrous apex inflammation or tumour causing sixth nerve palsy, ipsilateral fifth nerve facial pain, and otitis media with mastoiditis causing deafness. Mastoid infection is the classic cause.<br><br>CT petrous bone confirms the diagnosis. Aggressive antibiotic therapy and surgical drainage treat underlying mastoid infection.<br><br>Cavernous sinus (A) spares the eighth nerve. Pontine tegmentum (B) causes sixth and seventh nerve involvement. Cerebellopontine angle (C) causes fifth, seventh, eighth nerve involvement. Orbital apex (E) causes optic and third, fourth, sixth nerve involvement without eighth nerve.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old child presents with ipsilateral sixth nerve palsy and ipsilateral facial nerve palsy with no other neurological signs. MRI shows a pontine tumour. What is the most likely tumour?",o:["Medulloblastoma","Ependymoma","Diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma","Cerebellar astrocytoma","Craniopharyngioma"],a:2,e:"Diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma is the most common brainstem tumour in children causing progressive cranial nerve palsies including sixth and seventh nerve involvement. Prognosis is extremely poor.<br><br>Radiotherapy temporarily slows progression. Surgical resection is not feasible given the diffuse infiltrative nature of the tumour within the pons. Craniopharyngioma compressing the chiasm from below with calcification is a classic paediatric correlate.<br><br>Medulloblastoma (A) arises in the cerebellum. Ependymoma (B) arises from the fourth ventricle. Cerebellar astrocytoma (D) causes cerebellar ataxia not cranial nerve palsies primarily. Craniopharyngioma (E) is suprasellar causing visual field defects.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old woman presents with right eye proptosis, chemosis, and pulsatile bruit. She has limited adduction and abduction of the right eye with dilated episcleral vessels. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Orbital cellulitis","Sphenoid wing meningioma","Carotid-cavernous fistula","Thyroid eye disease"],a:3,e:"Carotid-cavernous fistula causes pulsatile proptosis, chemosis, dilated episcleral vessels, and an audible bruit from abnormal arteriovenous communication. Multiple cranial nerve palsies result from cavernous sinus involvement.<br><br>Endovascular embolisation is the definitive treatment. Intraocular pressure may be elevated from raised episcleral venous pressure. Pulsatile proptosis with bruit and corkscrew vessels pointing to a carotid-cavernous fistula is a classic triad.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (A) causes fever and sepsis. Orbital cellulitis (B) causes proptosis with fever but no bruit. Sphenoid wing meningioma (C) causes gradual proptosis without bruit. Thyroid eye disease (E) causes proptosis without bruit or dilated episcleral vessels.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old presents with sudden severe headache, neck stiffness, and third nerve palsy with pupil involvement. CT head is normal. What is the next most appropriate investigation?",o:["MRI brain with contrast","CT angiography of the cerebral vessels","Lumbar puncture for xanthochromia","Carotid Doppler ultrasound","Electroencephalography"],a:2,e:"When CT head is normal in suspected subarachnoid haemorrhage with thunderclap headache and third nerve palsy, lumbar puncture is mandatory. Xanthochromia confirms subarachnoid haemorrhage missed on CT.<br><br>CT angiography is then performed to identify the causative posterior communicating artery aneurysm for urgent neurosurgical management. A painful pupil-involving third nerve palsy raising aneurysm suspicion is a high-stakes emergency.<br><br>MRI brain (A) is less sensitive than LP for acute SAH. CT angiography (B) should follow LP confirmation. Carotid Doppler (D) is irrelevant for acute SAH. Electroencephalography (E) has no role in this presentation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with bilateral sixth nerve palsies and papilloedema. CT head shows no mass lesion. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Pontine glioma","Multiple sclerosis","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Myasthenia gravis"],a:3,e:"Bilateral sixth nerve palsy is a false localising sign of raised intracranial pressure. Combined with papilloedema and normal CT in an obese young woman, idiopathic intracranial hypertension is the diagnosis.<br><br>Lumbar puncture confirms elevated opening pressure above 25 cmH2O. Weight loss, acetazolamide, and lumboperitoneal shunting treat the condition. IIH in an obese young woman with papilledema and pulsatile tinnitus is a classic recognition vignette.<br><br>Cavernous sinus thrombosis (A) causes proptosis and fever. Pontine glioma (B) would show on CT or MRI. Multiple sclerosis (C) rarely causes bilateral sixth nerve palsy simultaneously. Myasthenia gravis (E) causes fatigable ptosis not papilloedema.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old presents with internuclear ophthalmoplegia showing failure of adduction of the right eye with nystagmus of the abducting left eye on left gaze. Where is the lesion?",o:["Right","Left abducens nucleus","Right abducens nucleus","Left medial longitudinal fasciculus","Right medial longitudinal fasciculus"],a:4,e:"Internuclear ophthalmoplegia results from a lesion of the medial longitudinal fasciculus. The MLF connects the contralateral sixth nucleus to the ipsilateral third nucleus. A right MLF lesion causes right adduction failure with left abducting nystagmus.<br><br>Multiple sclerosis is the most common cause in young adults. Brainstem stroke causes INO in older patients.<br><br>Left abducens nucleus (B) would cause horizontal gaze palsy. Right abducens nucleus (C) would cause right abduction failure. Left MLF (D) would cause left adduction failure. Right oculomotor nucleus (A) would cause right eye ophthalmoplegia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman presents with bilateral internuclear ophthalmoplegia. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Brainstem stroke","Multiple sclerosis","Pontine glioma","Wernicke encephalopathy","Cavernous sinus thrombosis"],a:1,e:"Bilateral internuclear ophthalmoplegia in a young woman is the classic presentation of multiple sclerosis affecting the bilateral medial longitudinal fasciculi in the pons. It is one of the most recognised neuro-ophthalmic signs of MS.<br><br>MRI brain reveals periventricular demyelinating plaques. Disease-modifying therapy reduces relapse frequency.<br><br>Brainstem stroke (A) typically causes unilateral INO. Pontine glioma (C) causes additional cranial nerve palsies. Wernicke encephalopathy (D) causes nystagmus and ophthalmoplegia from thiamine deficiency. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (E) causes painful ophthalmoplegia with proptosis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old presents with upgaze palsy, convergence retraction nystagmus, and light-near dissociation of the pupils. Where is the lesion?",o:["Cavernous sinus","Medulla","Pons","Midbrain tectum","Frontal lobe"],a:3,e:"Parinaud syndrome or dorsal midbrain syndrome causes upgaze palsy, convergence retraction nystagmus on attempted upgaze, and light-near dissociation. The pretectal area of the dorsal midbrain is the lesion site.<br><br>Causes include pineal region tumours, hydrocephalus, and midbrain stroke. Pupillary light-near dissociation results from pretectal disruption of the light reflex pathway. This is a recurring high-yield neuro-ophthalmology localisation worth recognising at a glance.<br><br>Cavernous sinus (A) causes third, fourth, sixth, and fifth nerve involvement. Pons (C) causes horizontal gaze palsy. Medulla (B) causes Wallenberg syndrome. Frontal lobe (E) causes contralateral gaze deviation not upgaze palsy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old presents with conjugate horizontal gaze deviation to the right with a left hemiplegia immediately after a stroke. Where is the lesion?",o:["Right occipital lobe","Left frontal lobe","Left pons","Right frontal lobe","Right pons"],a:3,e:"A right frontal lobe lesion destroys the frontal eye field causing the eyes to deviate toward the side of the lesion and away from the hemiplegia. The eyes look toward the lesion and away from the weakness.<br><br>The rule is: cortical lesions cause eyes to look at the lesion, pontine lesions cause eyes to look away from the lesion. Occipital PCA infarction producing macular-sparing homonymous hemianopia is a classic localiser.<br><br>Right occipital lobe (A) causes left homonymous hemianopia. Left frontal lobe (B) would cause left gaze deviation with right hemiplegia. Left pons (C) would cause right gaze deviation due to paramedian pontine reticular formation damage. Right pons (E) would cause left gaze deviation with right cranial nerve signs.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old presents with ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis on the right side. Which structure is damaged in complete Horner syndrome?",o:["Oculomotor nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Optic nerve","Sympathetic pathway","Facial nerve"],a:3,e:"Horner syndrome results from disruption of the three-neuron sympathetic pathway causing ipsilateral ptosis from Muller muscle weakness, miosis from dilator pupillae weakness, and anhidrosis from sudomotor fibre disruption.<br><br>Pharmacological testing with cocaine and apraclonidine confirms the diagnosis and localises the lesion to first, second, or third-order neurone. Horner syndrome with ptosis, miosis and anhidrosis localising the lesion is a recurring exam theme.<br><br>Oculomotor nerve (A) causes complete ptosis and mydriasis. Trigeminal nerve (B) causes facial sensory loss. Optic nerve (C) causes visual loss. Facial nerve (E) causes facial muscle weakness.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old presents with right Horner syndrome. Chest X-ray shows a right apical lung mass. Which neurone is affected in this Horner syndrome?",o:["First-order neurone","Third-order neurone","Postganglionic fibres only","Second-order neurone","Central neurone"],a:3,e:"A Pancoast tumour at the lung apex damages the second-order preganglionic sympathetic neurone as it descends from the ciliospinal centre of Budge in the spinal cord over the lung apex.<br><br>Hydroxyamphetamine eye drops confirm second-order neurone location by showing pupil dilation. MRI chest confirms the Pancoast tumour.<br><br>First-order neurone (A) lesions occur in the hypothalamus or brainstem. Third-order neurone (B) lesions occur along the internal carotid artery. Postganglionic fibres (C) is synonymous with third-order. Central neurone (E) is the same as first-order neurone.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with acute right Horner syndrome and ipsilateral face and contralateral body pain and temperature loss with dysphagia and ataxia. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Wallenberg lateral medullary syndrome","Weber syndrome","Foville syndrome","Parinaud syndrome","Benedikt syndrome"],a:0,e:"Wallenberg syndrome results from posterior inferior cerebellar artery occlusion causing lateral medullary infarction. Features include ipsilateral Horner syndrome, ipsilateral facial sensory loss, contralateral body pain and temperature loss, dysphagia, ataxia, and nystagmus.<br><br>The crossed sensory loss pattern is pathognomonic due to the spinothalamic tract and trigeminal nucleus involvement at different levels.<br><br>Weber syndrome (B) causes third nerve palsy with hemiplegia. Foville syndrome (C) involves pons. Parinaud syndrome (D) is dorsal midbrain. Benedikt syndrome (E) causes third nerve palsy with tremor.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old presents with right facial nerve palsy involving forehead sparing. He also has right upper motor neurone signs in the limbs. Where is the lesion?",o:["Right facial nerve nucleus in pons","Right petrous bone","Right parotid gland infiltrating facial nerve","Right cerebellopontine angle","Left upper motor neurone cortical lesion"],a:4,e:"Upper motor neurone facial palsy spares the forehead because the forehead muscles receive bilateral cortical innervation. A left cortical lesion causes right lower facial weakness with forehead sparing.<br><br>Lower motor neurone facial palsy involves forehead completely. Right limb UMN signs confirm the contralateral cortical lesion.<br><br>Right facial nerve nucleus (A) causes complete ipsilateral facial palsy including forehead. Right parotid (C) causes lower motor neurone palsy without limb signs. Cerebellopontine angle (D) causes complete lower motor neurone palsy. Right petrous bone (B) causes Bell palsy type complete lower motor neurone palsy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old presents with ipsilateral sixth nerve palsy, contralateral gaze deviation, and contralateral hemiplegia. Where is the lesion?",o:["Right frontal lobe","Cavernous sinus","Left paramedian pontine reticular formation","Right midbrain","Left cerebellopontine angle"],a:2,e:"A left PPRF lesion destroys the horizontal gaze centre causing inability to look left. Combined with left sixth nerve fascicle involvement and corticospinal tract damage this produces ipsilateral sixth nerve palsy, left gaze palsy, and right hemiplegia constituting Millard-Gubler syndrome variant.<br><br>Pontine lesions cause the eyes to look away from the side of the lesion and toward the hemiplegia.<br><br>Right frontal lobe (A) causes cortical gaze deviation toward the lesion. Cavernous sinus (B) causes painful ophthalmoplegia without hemiplegia. Right midbrain (D) causes Weber syndrome. Left cerebellopontine angle (E) causes fifth, seventh, and eighth nerve involvement.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with unilateral facial nerve palsy, sensorineural hearing loss, and a vesicular rash in the external auditory meatus. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Bell palsy","Acoustic neuroma","Parotid tumour","Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Lyme disease"],a:3,e:"Ramsay Hunt syndrome is caused by varicella zoster virus reactivation in the geniculate ganglion causing ipsilateral facial nerve palsy, sensorineural hearing loss, and vesicular rash in the external auditory meatus and pinna.<br><br>Oral acyclovir combined with prednisolone is the treatment. Prognosis is worse than Bell palsy with incomplete recovery in many patients.<br><br>Bell palsy (A) is idiopathic without rash or hearing loss. Acoustic neuroma (B) causes gradual hearing loss without facial palsy initially. Parotid tumour (C) causes lower motor neurone facial palsy without hearing loss or rash. Lyme disease (E) causes facial palsy without vesicular rash.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old presents with unilateral acute facial nerve palsy with no other neurological signs, no rash, and no hearing loss. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Lyme disease facial palsy","Sarcoid facial palsy","Acoustic neuroma","Bell palsy"],a:4,e:"Bell palsy is idiopathic lower motor neurone facial palsy causing complete unilateral facial weakness including forehead involvement. HSV reactivation is the most widely accepted aetiology.<br><br>Oral prednisolone within 72 hours improves recovery. Acyclovir combined with steroids provides additional benefit. Eye protection with lubricants and taping prevents exposure keratopathy.<br><br>Ramsay Hunt (A) has vesicular rash and hearing loss. Lyme disease (B) has tick exposure history. Sarcoid (C) causes bilateral facial palsy in Heerfordt syndrome. Acoustic neuroma (D) causes gradual onset hearing loss without acute facial palsy initially.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old presents with bilateral facial palsy, uveitis, parotid enlargement, and fever. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Lyme disease","Bell palsy","Myasthenia gravis","Heerfordt syndrome"],a:4,e:"Heerfordt syndrome is a manifestation of sarcoidosis comprising the tetrad of bilateral facial nerve palsy, uveitis, parotid enlargement, and fever. It is also called uveoparotid fever.<br><br>Serum ACE and chest imaging confirm sarcoidosis. Systemic corticosteroids treat both the facial palsy and uveitis simultaneously.<br><br>Ramsay Hunt (A) is unilateral with vesicular rash. Lyme disease (B) can cause facial palsy but not this tetrad. Bell palsy (C) is idiopathic and unilateral. Myasthenia gravis (D) causes fatigable ptosis and ophthalmoplegia not facial palsy and uveitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young female presents with painful loss of vision aggravated by eye movement and reduced color vision. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Optic neuritis","Acute glaucoma","Retinitis pigmentosa","Pituitary adenoma"],a:1,e:"Optic neuritis classically presents in young adults with acute unilateral visual loss, periocular pain worsened by eye movement, and dyschromatopsia. Relative afferent pupillary defect is commonly present.<br><br>Retrobulbar neuritis often demonstrates a normal optic disc initially.<br><br>Central retinal artery occlusion (A) produces sudden painless visual loss with cherry-red spot. Acute glaucoma (C) presents with corneal edema and markedly elevated intraocular pressure.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is most characteristic of optic neuritis in past-paper recall questions?",o:["Severe itching","Night blindness","Colored halos","Diplopia only","Pain on eye movement"],a:4,e:"Pain exacerbated by ocular movement is a classic symptom of optic neuritis because inflammation involves the optic nerve sheath and surrounding tissues.<br><br>Colored halos (C) suggest corneal edema in acute angle-closure glaucoma. Night blindness (B) is more typical of retinal degenerations like retinitis pigmentosa.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which disease is most strongly associated with optic neuritis?",o:["Diabetes mellitus","Rheumatoid arthritis","Hypertension","Multiple sclerosis","Myopia"],a:3,e:"Optic neuritis has a strong association with multiple sclerosis, especially demyelinating retrobulbar neuritis in young women.<br><br>MRI brain lesions significantly increase future risk of developing clinically definite multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Diabetes mellitus (A) more commonly causes ischemic optic neuropathy rather than demyelinating optic neuritis. Rheumatoid arthritis (B) is not the classic association.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with optic neuritis reports temporary worsening of vision after exercise or hot bath. This phenomenon is called:",o:["Argyll Robertson phenomenon","Uhthoff phenomenon","Marcus Gunn phenomenon","Foster Kennedy syndrome","Wernicke reaction"],a:1,e:"Uhthoff phenomenon refers to transient worsening of neurological symptoms, including visual impairment, after increased body temperature in demyelinating disease.<br><br>It is classically associated with optic neuritis and multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Marcus Gunn phenomenon (C) refers to relative afferent pupillary defect rather than heat-induced visual worsening. Foster Kennedy syndrome (D) involves optic atrophy with papilledema.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which pupillary abnormality is commonly present in unilateral optic neuritis?",o:["Argyll Robertson pupil","Relative afferent pupillary defect","Fixed dilated pupil","Horner syndrome","Adie tonic pupil"],a:1,e:"Relative afferent pupillary defect is commonly observed in unilateral or asymmetric optic neuritis because the diseased optic nerve conducts less afferent light stimulus.<br><br>The swinging flashlight test is the standard clinical method for detection.<br><br>Adie tonic pupil (E) affects parasympathetic pupillary innervation rather than optic nerve conduction. Horner syndrome (D) produces miosis and ptosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most important for evaluating demyelinating lesions in optic neuritis?",o:["Keratometry","Fluorescein angiography","Schirmer testing","Gonioscopy","MRI brain and orbit"],a:4,e:"MRI brain and orbit is the most important investigation in optic neuritis because it detects demyelinating plaques suggestive of multiple sclerosis.<br><br>The number of white matter lesions strongly predicts future MS risk.<br><br>Fluorescein angiography (B) evaluates retinal vascular disease rather than demyelinating optic nerve pathology. Keratometry (A) measures corneal curvature only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which type of optic neuritis shows normal optic disc appearance initially?",o:["Papillitis","Retrobulbar neuritis","Neuroretinitis","Ischemic papillopathy","Papilledema"],a:1,e:"Retrobulbar neuritis affects the posterior optic nerve, so the optic disc initially appears normal despite significant visual impairment.<br><br>The classic teaching is: \"The patient sees nothing, and the doctor sees nothing.\"<br><br>Papillitis (A) produces visible optic disc swelling. Papilledema (E) results from raised intracranial pressure rather than inflammatory demyelination.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual defect is commonly seen in optic neuritis?",o:["Bitemporal hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Homonymous hemianopia","Central scotoma","Altitudinal defect only"],a:3,e:"Central scotoma is the classic visual field defect in optic neuritis because papillomacular fibers are preferentially affected by demyelinating inflammation.<br><br>Patients often complain of blurred central vision and impaired color perception.<br><br>Bitemporal hemianopia (A) suggests optic chiasmal compression, commonly from pituitary adenoma. Homonymous hemianopia (C) indicates retrochiasmal lesions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which optic neuritis subtype is associated with optic disc swelling?",o:["Retrobulbar neuritis","Chiasmal neuritis","Toxic optic neuropathy","Optic atrophy","Papillitis"],a:4,e:"Papillitis is optic neuritis involving the optic nerve head and therefore produces visible optic disc edema on fundoscopy.<br><br>It is more common in children compared with retrobulbar neuritis.<br><br>Retrobulbar neuritis (A) initially demonstrates normal optic disc appearance because inflammation is posterior to the globe. Optic atrophy (D) represents chronic degeneration rather than acute inflammation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which color vision abnormality is most characteristic of optic neuritis?",o:["Tritanopia only","Red desaturation","Complete achromatopsia","Blue-yellow defect only","Monochromatism"],a:1,e:"Red desaturation is a classic early sign of optic neuritis because optic nerve dysfunction particularly affects color discrimination, especially red perception.<br><br>Patients often report colors appearing faded or washed out in the affected eye.<br><br>Complete achromatopsia (C) is uncommon in isolated optic neuritis and is more associated with congenital cone dysfunction disorders.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which treatment hastens recovery in acute demyelinating optic neuritis?",o:["Oral antibiotics only","Laser photocoagulation","Pilocarpine drops","Corneal transplantation","Intravenous corticosteroids"],a:4,e:"High-dose intravenous corticosteroids accelerate visual recovery in acute demyelinating optic neuritis, although long-term final visual outcome may remain similar.<br><br>The Optic Neuritis Treatment Trial is frequently tested in postgraduate ophthalmology recalls.<br><br>Pilocarpine (C) has no therapeutic role in optic neuritis. Laser photocoagulation (B) is used for retinal vascular diseases instead of optic nerve inflammation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature most strongly favors optic neuritis over ischemic optic neuropathy?",o:["Age above 70 years","Pain on eye movement","Altitudinal field defect","Sudden painless vision loss","Pale swollen optic disc"],a:1,e:"Pain worsened by ocular movement strongly favors optic neuritis because inflammatory demyelination affects the optic nerve sheath.<br><br>Optic neuritis commonly affects younger adults and is associated with multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Ischemic optic neuropathy usually presents as sudden painless visual loss with altitudinal field defect in older vasculopathic patients. Pale swollen optic disc (E) is more suggestive of ischemic disease.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which electrophysiological test is useful in optic neuritis?",o:["Electrooculography","Pachymetry","Electroretinography","Visual evoked potential","Tonography"],a:3,e:"Visual evoked potential demonstrates delayed P100 latency in optic neuritis due to slowed conduction along demyelinated optic nerve fibers.<br><br>It may detect subclinical demyelinating lesions even when visual acuity improves.<br><br>Electroretinography (C) evaluates retinal electrical activity rather than optic nerve conduction. Pachymetry (B) measures corneal thickness only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which sign is commonly seen after recovery from optic neuritis?",o:["Optic disc pallor","Hyphema","Cherry-red spot","Corneal edema","Retinal tear"],a:0,e:"Following recovery from optic neuritis, temporal optic disc pallor commonly develops because of secondary optic nerve fiber loss.<br><br>Visual acuity may improve substantially despite residual optic atrophy.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (C) is associated with central retinal artery occlusion. Corneal edema (D) occurs in acute glaucoma or endothelial dysfunction rather than optic neuritis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which symptom is most likely in bilateral optic neuritis in children?",o:["Leukocoria","Night blindness","Progressive proptosis","Colored halos","Severe bilateral visual loss"],a:4,e:"Pediatric optic neuritis more commonly presents bilaterally with severe visual impairment and marked optic disc swelling compared with adult disease.<br><br>Postviral demyelinating mechanisms are frequently implicated in children.<br><br>Leukocoria (A) suggests retinoblastoma or congenital cataract. Colored halos (D) are more typical of acute angle-closure glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which field defect is most characteristic of optic neuritis?",o:["Central scotoma","Homonymous hemianopia","Binasal hemianopia","Superior quadrantanopia","Peripheral ring scotoma"],a:0,e:"Central scotoma is the classic visual field defect in optic neuritis due to preferential involvement of papillomacular nerve fibers.<br><br>Patients often experience difficulty reading and recognizing faces because central vision is impaired.<br><br>Homonymous hemianopia (B) indicates retrochiasmal pathology rather than optic nerve inflammation. Peripheral ring scotoma (E) is more characteristic of retinal degeneration.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which condition is most strongly associated with recurrent optic neuritis and transverse myelitis?",o:["Neuromyelitis optica","Sarcoidosis","Behçet disease","Myasthenia gravis","Retinitis pigmentosa"],a:0,e:"Neuromyelitis optica is an autoimmune demyelinating disorder characterized by recurrent severe optic neuritis and transverse myelitis.<br><br>Aquaporin-4 antibody positivity is an important diagnostic marker.<br><br>Myasthenia gravis (D) causes neuromuscular junction dysfunction without optic nerve inflammation. Behçet disease (C) primarily causes retinal vasculitis and uveitis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which optic neuritis finding is considered a poor prognostic factor?",o:["Mild disc edema","Severe initial visual loss","Pain on eye movement","Female gender","Young age"],a:1,e:"Severe visual impairment at presentation is associated with poorer visual prognosis and greater axonal damage in optic neuritis.<br><br>Most patients nevertheless show substantial visual recovery over time despite initial profound vision loss.<br><br>Pain on eye movement (C) is common but not independently considered a major adverse prognostic indicator. Young age (E) generally favors better recovery.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which MRI finding increases future risk of multiple sclerosis after optic neuritis?",o:["Empty sella","Pituitary enlargement","White matter demyelinating plaques","Optic nerve calcification","Orbital cellulitis"],a:2,e:"MRI detection of cerebral white matter demyelinating plaques markedly increases future risk of clinically definite multiple sclerosis after optic neuritis.<br><br>Pituitary enlargement (B) suggests sellar pathology rather than demyelinating disease. Orbital cellulitis (E) is an infectious orbital disorder.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular sign may be demonstrated in unilateral optic neuritis using swinging flashlight test?",o:["Argyll Robertson pupil","Reverse Marcus Gunn jaw-winking","Fixed miotic pupil","Adie tonic pupil","Relative afferent pupillary defect"],a:4,e:"Relative afferent pupillary defect is detected by the swinging flashlight test when the affected optic nerve transmits reduced afferent light signals.<br><br>It is one of the most important bedside signs of unilateral optic neuritis.<br><br>Adie tonic pupil (D) is caused by parasympathetic denervation rather than optic nerve conduction abnormalities. Argyll Robertson pupil (A) is classically associated with neurosyphilis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which optic neuritis subtype is most commonly associated with multiple sclerosis?",o:["Neuroretinitis","Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy","Papilledema","Retrobulbar neuritis","Compressive optic neuropathy"],a:3,e:"Retrobulbar neuritis is the classic demyelinating optic neuritis associated with multiple sclerosis, particularly in young women.<br><br>Visual loss occurs despite initially normal optic disc appearance because inflammation lies posterior to the globe.<br><br>Papilledema (C) results from raised intracranial pressure rather than demyelinating optic nerve inflammation. Neuroretinitis (A) commonly follows infections.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which feature strongly favors neuroretinitis over typical demyelinating optic neuritis?",o:["Central scotoma","Macular star formation","Pain on eye movement","RAPD","Red desaturation"],a:1,e:"Neuroretinitis characteristically demonstrates optic disc edema followed by macular star exudates due to leakage from disc vasculature into the outer plexiform layer.<br><br>Cat-scratch disease is a classic infectious association.<br><br>Pain on eye movement (C) and red desaturation (E) are more characteristic of demyelinating optic neuritis than neuroretinitis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which antibody is associated with neuromyelitis optica spectrum disorder?",o:["Anti-dsDNA antibody","Rheumatoid factor","Anti-CCP antibody","Anti-Ro antibody","Aquaporin-4 antibody"],a:4,e:"Aquaporin-4 antibody positivity strongly supports diagnosis of neuromyelitis optica spectrum disorder, a condition characterized by severe recurrent optic neuritis and transverse myelitis.<br><br>Visual prognosis is generally worse than typical multiple sclerosis-related optic neuritis.<br><br>Anti-dsDNA antibody (A) is associated with systemic lupus erythematosus rather than neuromyelitis optica. Rheumatoid factor (B) relates to rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual symptom often persists despite good visual acuity recovery after optic neuritis?",o:["Diplopia","Reduced contrast sensitivity","Nyctalopia","Colored halos","Photopsia only"],a:1,e:"Patients recovering from optic neuritis may regain excellent Snellen visual acuity yet continue to experience reduced contrast sensitivity and impaired color vision.<br><br>These residual deficits reflect persistent optic nerve dysfunction despite apparent clinical recovery.<br><br>Nyctalopia (C) is more characteristic of retinal degenerations. Diplopia (A) usually results from ocular motor nerve dysfunction rather than isolated optic neuritis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which optic neuritis characteristic is commonly emphasized in FCPS recall questions?",o:["Sudden painless blindness","Marked proptosis","Corneal ulceration","Young female patient","Lens subluxation"],a:3,e:"Typical demyelinating optic neuritis most commonly affects young adult females and is strongly associated with multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Sudden painless blindness (A) favors vascular occlusive disease rather than inflammatory demyelinating optic neuropathy. Lens subluxation (E) occurs in connective tissue disorders.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which fundoscopic finding is typical in retrobulbar neuritis during the acute stage?",o:["Severe papilledema","Vitreous hemorrhage","Cherry-red spot","Macular hole","Normal optic disc"],a:4,e:"Retrobulbar neuritis initially demonstrates a normal optic disc because inflammation involves the posterior intraorbital optic nerve.<br><br>The classic phrase remains highly tested in ophthalmology examinations: \"The patient sees nothing, and the doctor sees nothing.\"<br><br>Cherry-red spot (C) occurs in central retinal artery occlusion. Severe papilledema (A) suggests raised intracranial pressure.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation best predicts conversion from optic neuritis to multiple sclerosis?",o:["MRI brain","OCT cornea","Tonography","Keratometry","Schirmer test"],a:0,e:"MRI brain is the strongest predictor of future multiple sclerosis development following optic neuritis because demyelinating plaques indicate disseminated CNS disease.<br><br>Patients with multiple white matter lesions have significantly higher conversion risk.<br><br>Keratometry (D) measures corneal curvature and has no role in demyelinating disease assessment. Schirmer testing (E) evaluates tear secretion only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which disease may mimic optic neuritis but usually affects older patients with vascular risk factors?",o:["Macular degeneration","Keratoconus","Retinitis pigmentosa","Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy","Endophthalmitis"],a:3,e:"Anterior ischemic optic neuropathy commonly affects older individuals with hypertension, diabetes, or giant cell arteritis and may resemble optic neuritis clinically.<br><br>However, visual loss is usually painless and associated with swollen pale optic disc.<br><br>Keratoconus (B) is a corneal ectatic disorder and does not cause acute optic nerve dysfunction. Endophthalmitis (E) produces severe ocular inflammation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which retinal finding is absent in pure optic neuritis?",o:["Relative afferent pupillary defect","Central scotoma","Cherry-red spot","Dyschromatopsia","Pain on eye movement"],a:2,e:"Cherry-red spot is characteristic of central retinal artery occlusion and is not a feature of optic neuritis.<br><br>Optic neuritis instead produces painful visual loss, central scotoma, dyschromatopsia, and RAPD.<br><br>Pain on eye movement (E) and impaired color vision (D) are classic manifestations of demyelinating optic nerve inflammation.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding optic neuritis is most accurate?",o:["It usually causes permanent total blindness","Visual recovery is generally good","It is unrelated to multiple sclerosis","Pain is absent in most cases","It commonly affects elderly diabetic patients"],a:1,e:"Most patients with typical demyelinating optic neuritis experience substantial spontaneous visual recovery over weeks to months, even without treatment.<br><br>Intravenous corticosteroids mainly accelerate recovery rather than improving ultimate visual outcome.<br><br>Permanent total blindness (A) is uncommon in typical optic neuritis. The disease is strongly associated with multiple sclerosis, especially in young women.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old obese woman presents with headache, blurred vision, and bilateral disc swelling. CT head is normal. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Malignant hypertension","Optic neuritis bilateral","Compressive optic neuropathy"],a:0,e:"IIH classically affects obese young women presenting with headache, pulsatile tinnitus, transient visual obscurations, and bilateral papilloedema. CT head is normal with no mass lesion.<br><br>Lumbar puncture confirms elevated opening pressure above 25 cmH2O with normal CSF constituents.<br><br>Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (B) requires MR venography to exclude. Malignant hypertension (C) causes bilateral disc swelling with elevated blood pressure. Bilateral optic neuritis (D) causes reduced vision and pain. Compressive neuropathy (E) is typically unilateral.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old with IIH presents with progressively enlarged blind spots on visual field testing. Which visual field defect is the earliest and most characteristic finding in papilloedema?",o:["Central scotoma","Bitemporal hemianopia","Inferior nasal step","Altitudinal field defect","Enlarged blind spot"],a:4,e:"Enlarged blind spot is the earliest visual field defect in papilloedema caused by oedema displacing peripapillary photoreceptors. Central visual acuity is typically preserved initially despite the blind spot enlargement.<br><br>Progressive loss of the inferior nasal quadrant follows as chronic papilloedema causes permanent nerve fibre layer damage.<br><br>Central scotoma (A) occurs in optic neuritis. Inferior nasal step (C) is characteristic of glaucoma. Altitudinal defect (D) occurs in ischaemic optic neuropathy. Bitemporal hemianopia (B) indicates chiasmal compression.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling. Slit-lamp shows absent venous pulsations. What is the significance of absent spontaneous venous pulsations?",o:["Normal finding in all patients","Indicates low intracranial pressure","Suggests raised intracranial pressure above 200 mmH2O","Confirms optic neuritis diagnosis","Indicates retinal vein occlusion"],a:2,e:"Spontaneous venous pulsations are absent when intracranial pressure exceeds 200 mmH2O. Their presence effectively excludes significantly raised ICP. Their absence is an important early indicator of papilloedema.<br><br>Spontaneous venous pulsations are visible in approximately 80% of normal individuals at the disc margin.<br><br>Normal finding (A) is incorrect as SVPs are absent in 20% of normal individuals. Low ICP (B) is the opposite. Optic neuritis (D) does not specifically cause absent SVPs. Retinal vein occlusion (E) causes venous engorgement not absent pulsations.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling, sixth nerve palsy, and pulsatile tinnitus. MRI is normal. What investigation confirms the diagnosis of IIH?",o:["CT head with contrast","MR venography of cerebral sinuses","Electroencephalography","Lumbar puncture measuring opening pressure","Carotid Doppler ultrasound"],a:3,e:"Lumbar puncture confirming opening pressure above 25 cmH2O with normal CSF constituents is diagnostic of IIH. The sixth nerve palsy is a false localising sign of raised intracranial pressure.<br><br>CSF examination excludes infectious or inflammatory causes of raised ICP before confirming the idiopathic diagnosis.<br><br>CT with contrast (A) excludes mass lesions but does not confirm IIH. MR venography (B) excludes cerebral venous sinus thrombosis. Electroencephalography (C) has no role. Carotid Doppler (E) is irrelevant to IIH diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 32-year-old woman with IIH is failing medical therapy. She has progressive visual field loss. Which surgical intervention is most appropriate to protect vision?",o:["Ventriculoperitoneal shunt only","Optic nerve sheath fenestration","Lumboperitoneal shunt only","Cerebral venous stenting","Optic nerve"],a:4,e:"Both optic nerve sheath fenestration and CSF shunting procedures are accepted surgical treatments for progressive visual loss in IIH failing medical therapy. ONSF directly decompresses the optic nerve. Shunting reduces overall ICP.<br><br>ONSF is preferred when visual loss is the primary concern. LP shunting or VP shunting addresses the headache component more effectively.<br><br>VP shunt only (A) is one option but not the complete answer. ONSF alone (B) is incomplete. LP shunt only (C) is incomplete. Cerebral venous stenting (D) is emerging for venous sinus stenosis but not yet standard practice.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old is referred with bilateral disc swelling. Blood pressure is 240/140 mmHg. Fundoscopy shows bilateral disc oedema, flame haemorrhages, cotton wool spots, and macular star. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy","Central retinal vein occlusion","IIH","Diabetic papillopathy","Malignant hypertension"],a:4,e:"Malignant hypertension causes bilateral disc swelling from severely elevated ICP and direct ischaemia. The macular star from lipid exudate along Henle fibre layer combined with disc oedema is pathognomonic.<br><br>Urgent blood pressure reduction, excluding hypertensive encephalopathy, is the immediate management priority. Gradual not rapid BP reduction prevents ischaemic complications.<br><br>Central retinal vein occlusion (B) causes unilateral disc swelling. IIH (C) occurs in normotensive patients. Diabetic papillopathy (D) occurs in diabetics without severe hypertension. AION (A) causes unilateral disc swelling with altitudinal field defect.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old woman on long-term tetracycline for acne rosacea develops headache and bilateral disc swelling. What is the drug-induced cause of papilloedema?",o:["Tetracycline-induced raised intracranial pressure","Tetracycline-induced optic neuritis","Tetracycline-induced retinal toxicity","Tetracycline-induced anterior uveitis","Tetracycline"],a:0,e:"Tetracycline and its derivatives including doxycycline and minocycline can cause drug-induced IIH by impairing CSF absorption. Immediate drug withdrawal resolves the papilloedema in most cases.<br><br>Other drugs causing IIH include vitamin A derivatives including isotretinoin, steroids on withdrawal, and nitrofurantoin.<br><br>Optic neuritis (B) is not caused by tetracycline. Retinal toxicity (C) is caused by hydroxychloroquine and vigabatrin. Anterior uveitis (D) is caused by rifabutin. Corneal deposits (E) are caused by amiodarone.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 22-year-old on isotretinoin for acne develops headache and bilateral disc swelling. What is the mechanism of isotretinoin-induced intracranial hypertension?",o:["Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Impaired CSF absorption at the arachnoid granulations","Cerebral oedema from hepatotoxicity","Direct optic nerve compression","Choroid plexus hypersecretion of CSF"],a:1,e:"Isotretinoin, a vitamin A derivative, impairs CSF absorption at the arachnoid granulations causing raised intracranial pressure and papilloedema. The mechanism is identical to hypervitaminosis A-induced IIH.<br><br>Drug withdrawal is mandatory. The papilloedema and raised ICP typically resolve after stopping isotretinoin, though acetazolamide may be required during the transition period.<br><br>Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (A) is a separate cause excluded by MR venography. Hepatotoxicity (C) does not cause cerebral oedema. Direct optic nerve compression (D) causes unilateral not bilateral disc swelling. Choroid plexus hypersecretion (E) is not the mechanism.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling, dilated cerebral veins on MRI, and a history of ear infection. What investigation is most important?",o:["CT head plain","Lumbar puncture immediately","MR venography of cerebral sinuses","Carotid angiography","Electroencephalography"],a:2,e:"Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis must be excluded in bilateral papilloedema with a history of ear infection or mastoiditis. Lateral sinus thrombosis from otitis media is a well-recognised cause of secondary intracranial hypertension.<br><br>MR venography demonstrates absent flow in the thrombosed sinus confirming the diagnosis before anticoagulation is initiated.<br><br>Plain CT (A) may miss venous sinus thrombosis. Immediate LP (B) is dangerous before excluding thrombosis. Carotid angiography (D) is not indicated. Electroencephalography (E) has no role in this clinical scenario.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"The Foster Kennedy syndrome consists of which combination of findings?",o:["Bilateral disc swelling with bilateral optic atrophy","Unilateral disc swelling with ipsilateral optic atrophy","Bilateral optic atrophy with normal discs","Ipsilateral optic atrophy and contralateral papilloedema","Bilateral papilloedema with central scotomas bilaterally"],a:3,e:"Foster Kennedy syndrome consists of ipsilateral optic atrophy from direct nerve compression with contralateral papilloedema from raised ICP. Olfactory groove meningioma is the classic cause compressing the ipsilateral optic nerve directly.<br><br>Pseudo-Foster Kennedy syndrome shows sequential bilateral optic disc swelling with one disc becoming atrophic from bilateral ischaemic optic neuropathy.<br><br>Bilateral disc swelling (A) is papilloedema without atrophy. Unilateral disc swelling with ipsilateral atrophy (B) is the reverse pattern. Bilateral optic atrophy (C) represents end-stage damage. Bilateral papilloedema with scotomas (E) suggests bilateral optic neuritis.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old presents with headache and bilateral disc swelling. MRI shows empty sella. What does an empty sella indicate in IIH?",o:["Pituitary adenoma","Hypothalamic tumour","Normal variant unrelated to IIH","Craniopharyngioma","Transmitted CSF pulsations causing"],a:4,e:"Empty sella on MRI in IIH represents arachnoid herniation into the pituitary fossa from chronically elevated CSF pulsations. It supports but does not confirm the diagnosis of raised intracranial pressure.<br><br>The finding is seen in approximately 70% of IIH patients and reflects the mechanical effects of chronically elevated intracranial pressure on sellar anatomy.<br><br>Pituitary adenoma (A) causes a filled enlarged sella. Hypothalamic tumour (B) is a separate diagnosis. Normal variant (C) is incorrect as it is associated with IIH. Craniopharyngioma (D) causes suprasellar calcification.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old woman with IIH is started on acetazolamide. What is the mechanism of action of acetazolamide in reducing intracranial pressure?",o:["Reduces cerebral blood flow","Direct vasoconstrictive effect on cerebral vessels","Diuretic action reducing total body fluid","Increases CSF absorption at the arachnoid granulations","Reduces cerebral"],a:3,e:"Acetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor that reduces CSF production by the choroid plexus and increases absorption at the arachnoid granulations. This reduces intracranial pressure in IIH.<br><br>Weight loss remains the most effective long-term management. Topiramate has the dual benefit of reducing ICP and causing weight loss making it a useful adjunct.<br><br>Reducing cerebral blood flow (A) is not the mechanism. Diuretic action (C) is a secondary effect not the primary ICP mechanism. Cerebral vasoconstriction (B) is not how acetazolamide works. Osmotic effect (E) describes mannitol action.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old man presents with bilateral disc swelling and normal blood pressure. MRI shows a posterior fossa tumour. Which specific mechanism causes papilloedema in this case?",o:["Direct tumour invasion of optic nerves","Paraneoplastic optic neuropathy","Obstructive hydrocephalus blocking CSF flow","Tumour-secreted toxins affecting the discs","Cerebral venous thrombosis"],a:2,e:"Posterior fossa tumours obstruct CSF flow at the fourth ventricle or cerebral aqueduct causing obstructive hydrocephalus. The resulting raised ICP transmits through the optic nerve sheaths causing bilateral papilloedema.<br><br>Emergency management includes dexamethasone to reduce surrounding oedema and urgent neurosurgical referral for decompression or ventricular drainage.<br><br>Direct tumour invasion (A) would cause unilateral disc swelling. Paraneoplastic optic neuropathy (B) causes visual loss without disc swelling. Tumour toxins (D) do not cause papilloedema. Venous thrombosis (E) is a separate mechanism requiring MR venography.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old presents with acute bilateral disc swelling, headache, and reduced vision to 6/60 bilaterally. VEPs show markedly prolonged latencies. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Papilloedema from IIH","Bilateral","Malignant hypertension","Leber hereditary optic neuropathy","Bilateral simultaneous optic neuritis"],a:4,e:"Bilateral simultaneous optic neuritis with markedly prolonged VEP latencies, acute disc swelling, and significantly reduced vision distinguishes it from papilloedema which typically preserves central acuity. NMO spectrum disorder must be excluded with AQP4-IgG serology.<br><br>Intravenous methylprednisolone accelerates visual recovery. MOG-antibody disease is another important cause of bilateral simultaneous optic neuritis.<br><br>IIH papilloedema (A) preserves central vision initially. Malignant hypertension (C) requires severely elevated BP. Leber HON (D) is painless and typically sequential not simultaneous bilateral. AION (B) causes altitudinal field defect in older vascular patients.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 25-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling. On OCT the peripapillary retinal nerve fibre layer shows a donut pattern of thickening. Which stage of papilloedema does this represent?",o:["Atrophic stage","Chronic established stage","Early papilloedema","Pre-papilloedema","Vintage papilloedema with drusen"],a:2,e:"OCT showing peripapillary RNFL thickening in a donut distribution represents early papilloedema before clinical disc swelling becomes apparent on fundoscopy. OCT is more sensitive than clinical examination for detecting early papilloedema.<br><br>Serial OCT monitoring of RNFL thickness tracks treatment response and detects developing optic atrophy from chronic papilloedema before irreversible vision loss occurs.<br><br>Atrophic stage (A) shows RNFL thinning not thickening. Chronic established stage (B) shows more uniform swelling with haemorrhages. Pre-papilloedema (D) shows no OCT changes. Vintage papilloedema (E) shows calcified drusen masquerading as disc swelling.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling and a systemic diagnosis of sarcoidosis. What specific finding on fundoscopy suggests sarcoid-related disc swelling rather than papilloedema from raised ICP?",o:["Bilateral symmetrical disc elevation","Absence of haemorrhages at the disc","Spontaneous venous pulsations present","Periphlebitis and candle wax dripping alongside disc swelling","Enlarged blind spot on"],a:3,e:"Sarcoid granulomatous infiltration of the optic disc and retinal periphlebitis with candle wax dripping indicates direct infiltrative disc involvement rather than raised ICP papilloedema. Disc swelling in sarcoidosis may result from either mechanism.<br><br>Serum ACE, chest CT, and CSF examination help distinguish infiltrative sarcoid optic neuropathy from sarcoid-associated intracranial hypertension.<br><br>Bilateral symmetrical elevation (A) occurs in both. Absence of haemorrhages (B) is non-specific. SVPs present (C) do not exclude disc swelling. Enlarged blind spot (E) occurs in both conditions.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with unilateral disc swelling and normal vision. Ultrasound of the disc shows high reflectivity calcified nodules within the disc substance. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Papilloedema","Anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy","Optic disc drusen","Optic nerve meningioma","Papillitis"],a:2,e:"Optic disc drusen are calcified hyaline bodies within the disc substance causing pseudopapilloedema. High reflectivity on B-scan ultrasound and autofluorescence on fundus photography confirm the diagnosis and exclude true papilloedema.<br><br>Disc drusen can compress axons causing peripheral visual field loss. Associated complications include anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy.<br><br>Papilloedema (A) shows no calcification on ultrasound. AION (B) causes acute visual loss with altitudinal defect. Optic nerve meningioma (D) causes progressive visual loss with optociliary shunts. Papillitis (E) causes disc swelling with reduced vision and pain.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 26-year-old woman presents with bilateral disc swelling, transient visual obscurations lasting seconds, and pulsatile tinnitus. Visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally. What is causing the transient visual obscurations?",o:["Migraine aura from raised ICP","Transient ischaemia of the optic nerves from momentary ICP spikes","Retinal artery spasm","Posterior vitreous detachment","Cerebral vasospasm"],a:1,e:"Transient visual obscurations in papilloedema are brief seconds-long visual blackouts caused by transient ischaemia of the swollen optic nerve head from momentary ICP spikes, often triggered by postural changes or Valsalva manoeuvre.<br><br>They are an important symptom indicating severe papilloedema requiring urgent treatment escalation to prevent permanent visual loss from chronic optic nerve compression.<br><br>Migraine aura (A) lasts 20 to 30 minutes not seconds. Retinal artery spasm (C) is not associated with IIH. Posterior vitreous detachment (D) causes floaters. Cerebral vasospasm (E) causes focal neurological deficits not transient visual blackouts.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 55-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling, bilateral sixth nerve palsies, and diplopia. CT head shows enlarged ventricles. What is the diagnosis?",o:["Hydrocephalus causing raised intracranial pressure","Normal pressure hydrocephalus","IIH in an obese woman","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Brainstem encephalitis"],a:0,e:"Bilateral sixth nerve palsies as false localising signs combined with papilloedema and enlarged ventricles on CT confirm obstructive hydrocephalus as the cause of raised intracranial pressure. The aqueduct or fourth ventricular outlet may be obstructed.<br><br>Urgent neurosurgical referral for ventricular drainage or shunting is required. Dexamethasone reduces peritumoural oedema while awaiting surgery.<br><br>Normal pressure hydrocephalus (B) causes the triad of dementia, ataxia, and incontinence without papilloedema. IIH (C) shows normal or slit ventricles. Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (D) requires MR venography. Brainstem encephalitis (E) causes specific brainstem signs.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old presents with papilloedema and is found to have SLE. Anti-phospholipid antibodies are positive. What mechanism is most likely causing the raised intracranial pressure?",o:["Lupus cerebritis causing cerebral oedema","Hydroxychloroquine toxicity causing IIH","Corticosteroid withdrawal-induced IIH","SLE-related optic neuritis causing disc swelling","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis from antiphospholipid syndrome"],a:4,e:"Antiphospholipid syndrome in SLE causes a hypercoagulable state predisposing to cerebral venous sinus thrombosis. This obstructs CSF absorption causing secondary intracranial hypertension and papilloedema.<br><br>MR venography confirms the thrombosis. Anticoagulation with heparin followed by warfarin is the treatment. Underlying SLE requires immunosuppression.<br><br>Lupus cerebritis (A) causes encephalopathy not papilloedema predominantly. Steroid withdrawal IIH (C) is possible but less likely with positive antiphospholipid antibodies. Optic neuritis (D) causes visual loss not papilloedema. Hydroxychloroquine (B) does not cause IIH.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling and a history of taking high-dose vitamin A supplements. What is the mechanism of vitamin A-induced intracranial hypertension?",o:["Direct optic nerve toxicity","Choroid plexus hypersecretion of CSF","Impaired CSF absorption at arachnoid granulations","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Pseudotumour cerebri from hepatotoxicity"],a:2,e:"Hypervitaminosis A impairs CSF absorption at the arachnoid granulations causing secondary intracranial hypertension and papilloedema. Isotretinoin and retinol supplements are the most common vitamin A-related causes in clinical practice.<br><br>Stopping the supplement resolves raised ICP. Acetazolamide may be required during the recovery period. Chronic hypervitaminosis A also causes hepatotoxicity requiring liver function monitoring.<br><br>Direct optic nerve toxicity (A) is not the mechanism. Choroid plexus hypersecretion (B) is not caused by vitamin A. Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (D) is a separate mechanism. Hepatotoxicity (E) does not directly cause IIH.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 20-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling. He is not obese and has no systemic disease identified. MRI and MR venography are normal. CSF pressure is 32 cmH2O with normal constituents. What diagnosis does he meet criteria for?",o:["Secondary intracranial hypertension","Normal pressure hydrocephalus","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Optic disc drusen mimicking papilloedema"],a:2,e:"IIH can occur in males and non-obese individuals, though less commonly. The modified Dandy criteria require papilloedema, raised ICP above 25 cmH2O with normal CSF, normal neuroimaging, and no secondary cause identified.<br><br>Male IIH is associated with weight gain even without obesity and carries higher visual morbidity than female IIH.<br><br>Secondary intracranial hypertension (A) requires an identifiable cause. Normal pressure hydrocephalus (B) causes the gait-cognition-continence triad. Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (D) is excluded by MR venography. Disc drusen (E) are excluded by OCT and ultrasound.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 40-year-old presents with chronic papilloedema. OCT shows progressive RNFL thinning over 18 months. What does progressive RNFL thinning indicate in this context?",o:["Resolution of papilloedema indicating treatment success","Normal ageing-related RNFL loss","Glaucomatous damage from elevated IOP","Secondary optic atrophy from chronic papilloedema","Retinal pigmentary"],a:3,e:"Progressive RNFL thinning on serial OCT in chronic papilloedema indicates developing secondary optic atrophy from axonal death caused by sustained optic nerve compression. This signals impending irreversible visual field loss.<br><br>Urgent escalation of ICP management is required. Optic nerve sheath fenestration or CSF shunting is indicated to prevent further permanent visual loss.<br><br>RNFL thinning does not indicate resolution (A) but deterioration. Normal ageing (B) causes mild thinning not progressive rapid loss. Glaucoma (C) requires elevated IOP as the cause. Retinal pigmentary degeneration (E) causes different field patterns.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 45-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling after recent head trauma. CT shows bilateral subdural haematomas. What is the mechanism of papilloedema?",o:["Direct traumatic optic nerve injury","Cerebral contusion causing focal oedema","Drug-induced IIH from post-trauma medications","Raised ICP from haematoma mass effect and brain shift","Cerebral vasospasm"],a:3,e:"Bilateral subdural haematomas cause raised ICP through mass effect and midline shift. The transmitted pressure through the optic nerve sheaths causes bilateral papilloedema. Urgent neurosurgical evacuation of haematomas reduces ICP.<br><br>Pupillary examination is critical in these patients as a fixed dilated pupil indicates uncal herniation requiring immediate neurosurgical intervention.<br><br>Direct traumatic optic nerve injury (A) causes unilateral disc pallor not bilateral swelling. Focal contusion oedema (B) causes focal neurological signs. Drug-induced IIH (C) is not caused by trauma medications. Cerebral vasospasm (E) is a delayed complication of subarachnoid haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old with bilateral disc swelling is found to have bilateral transverse sinus stenosis on MR venography. What is the relationship between venous sinus stenosis and IIH?",o:["Venous sinus stenosis is unrelated to IIH","Stenosis is always the primary cause of IIH","Stenosis causes venous hypertension impairing CSF absorption","Stenosis is a coincidental radiological finding only","Stenosis only occurs in secondary intracranial hypertension"],a:2,e:"Transverse sinus stenosis causes venous hypertension that impairs CSF absorption at the arachnoid granulations. Whether stenosis is a primary cause or consequence of raised ICP remains debated. Venous stenting is an emerging treatment for stenosis-associated IIH.<br><br>The chicken and egg relationship means both mechanisms likely contribute in a positive feedback cycle of raised ICP worsening stenosis.<br><br>Unrelated to IIH (A) is incorrect. Always primary cause (B) is unproven. Coincidental finding only (D) is incorrect as it is clinically significant. Only in secondary IIH (E) is incorrect as it occurs in idiopathic cases.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 32-year-old woman with IIH has CSF opening pressure of 40 cmH2O. She has severe headache but normal visual acuity and visual fields. What is the first-line medical treatment?",o:["Furosemide","Intravenous mannitol","Topiramate alone","Acetazolamide","Intravenous dexamethasone"],a:3,e:"Acetazolamide is the first-line medical treatment for IIH. It reduces CSF production through carbonic anhydrase inhibition. Starting dose is 500 mg twice daily titrated to 2 to 4 grams daily as tolerated.<br><br>Weight loss of 5 to 10% reduces ICP significantly. The combination of acetazolamide and dietary weight loss is more effective than either alone.<br><br>Furosemide (A) is a second-line adjunct. Topiramate alone (C) is useful as adjunct due to weight loss effect. Intravenous mannitol (B) is for acute ICP crises. Intravenous dexamethasone (E) is used for tumour-related raised ICP not IIH.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old with bilateral disc swelling develops visual field loss progressing to an inferior arcuate scotoma. What does this field pattern suggest?",o:["Pituitary adenoma compressing the chiasm","Glaucomatous damage mimicking papilloedema","Chronic papilloedema causing superior nerve fibre loss first","Occipital lobe infarction","Retinal detachment"],a:2,e:"Chronic papilloedema preferentially damages the inferior and nasal nerve fibres first causing superior arcuate and inferior nasal step defects. Progressive superior field loss as inferior RNFL is compressed indicates worsening optic nerve damage from chronic raised ICP.<br><br>The pattern of field loss in chronic papilloedema progresses from peripheral constriction to arcuate scotomas to central vision loss in end-stage disease.<br><br>Pituitary adenoma (A) causes bitemporal hemianopia. Glaucoma (B) causes similar field patterns but without bilateral disc swelling from raised ICP. Occipital infarction (D) causes homonymous hemianopia. Retinal detachment (E) causes a field defect corresponding to detachment location.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 35-year-old presents with bilateral disc swelling and is found to have polycythaemia vera. What is the mechanism of papilloedema in this condition?",o:["Hyperviscosity causing cerebral venous thrombosis","Anaemia from bone marrow suppression","Direct erythrocyte infiltration of the optic nerve","EPO excess causing direct disc swelling","Secondary"],a:0,e:"Polycythaemia vera causes hyperviscosity predisposing to cerebral venous sinus thrombosis. Obstructed venous drainage raises ICP causing bilateral papilloedema. Venesection and cytoreductive therapy reduce viscosity and thrombotic risk.<br><br>MR venography confirms the venous sinus thrombosis. Anticoagulation is required alongside management of the underlying polycythaemia.<br><br>Anaemia (B) is not a feature of polycythaemia. Erythrocyte infiltration (C) does not occur. EPO excess (D) does not directly cause disc swelling. Secondary hypertension (E) is not the primary mechanism in polycythaemia-related papilloedema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 60-year-old presents with unilateral disc swelling, progressive visual loss, and optociliary shunt vessels on the disc. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Papilloedema from raised ICP","Central retinal vein occlusion","Anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy","Optic disc drusen","Optic nerve"],a:4,e:"Optociliary shunt vessels on the disc are pathognomonic of optic nerve meningioma. These vessels develop as collateral channels bypassing obstruction of the central retinal vein by the meningioma. Progressive unilateral visual loss with a positive RAPD confirms optic nerve compression.<br><br>MRI with gadolinium shows the classic tram-track sign of meningeal enhancement along the optic nerve sheath.<br><br>IIH papilloedema (A) is bilateral. Central retinal vein occlusion (B) causes flame haemorrhages without optociliary shunts. AION (C) causes acute disc swelling with altitudinal field defect. Disc drusen (D) cause pseudopapilloedema without optociliary shunts.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old woman with IIH undergoes optic nerve sheath fenestration. Which complication is most specific to this procedure?",o:["Central retinal artery occlusion","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Sympathetic ophthalmia","Worsening intracranial hypertension","Corneal decompensation"],a:3,e:"Optic nerve sheath fenestration decompresses the optic nerve locally but does not reduce systemic intracranial pressure. Headaches may worsen or persist after ONSF. CSF shunting procedures are more effective for managing refractory headache.<br><br>The procedure protects vision by locally reducing the pressure around the optic nerve. Contralateral visual improvement may occur through unclear mechanisms.<br><br>Central retinal artery occlusion (A) can occur from operative trauma but is an uncommon technical mishap rather than the characteristic limitation of the procedure. Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis (B) is unrelated to local nerve sheath surgery. Sympathetic ophthalmia (C) follows penetrating uveal trauma, and corneal decompensation (E) relates to endothelial damage, neither of which results from optic nerve sheath fenestration.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old farmer presents with a pearly nodular lesion with rolled edges and telangiectatic vessels near the lower eyelid. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Chalazion","Melanoma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is the most common malignant eyelid tumor and classically presents as a pearly nodular lesion with rolled margins and surface telangiectasia.<br><br>The lower eyelid and medial canthus are common sites due to chronic ultraviolet exposure.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) often mimics recurrent chalazion and is more aggressive. Squamous cell carcinoma (C) typically demonstrates ulceration and keratinization.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with leukocoria and strabismus. CT scan shows intraocular calcification. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Coats disease","Retinoblastoma","Persistent fetal vasculature","Retinopathy of prematurity"],a:2,e:"Retinoblastoma is the most common primary intraocular malignant tumor of childhood and classically presents with leukocoria and strabismus.<br><br>Intraocular calcification on CT imaging is a highly characteristic feature.<br><br>Coats disease (B) may produce leukocoria but typically lacks calcification. Choroidal melanoma (A) mainly affects adults.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent unilateral chalazion in an elderly patient should raise suspicion for:",o:["Hemangioma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Neurofibroma","Papilloma"],a:1,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma is a highly malignant eyelid tumor that frequently masquerades as recurrent chalazion or chronic unilateral blepharoconjunctivitis.<br><br>Upper eyelid involvement is common because of numerous meibomian glands.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (C) usually presents as pearly nodular lesions rather than recurrent inflammatory-appearing chalazia. Hemangioma (A) is benign vascular proliferation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A young woman presents with unilateral progressive proptosis. CT demonstrates a well-circumscribed intraconal lesion. Which orbital tumor is most likely?",o:["Cavernous hemangioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Lymphoma","Optic glioma","Dermoid cyst"],a:0,e:"Cavernous hemangioma is the most common benign orbital tumor in adults and classically causes painless slowly progressive axial proptosis.<br><br>Imaging demonstrates a well-defined intraconal vascular lesion.<br><br>Rhabdomyosarcoma (B) usually presents rapidly in children with painful proptosis. Optic glioma (D) commonly affects pediatric patients.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which malignant eyelid tumor is most strongly associated with local tissue destruction but rare metastasis?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Merkel cell carcinoma"],a:2,e:"Basal cell carcinoma is locally invasive and destructive but metastasizes very rarely. It commonly affects the lower eyelid and medial canthus.<br><br>Delayed treatment may produce extensive orbital invasion and tissue destruction.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) and melanoma (D) carry greater metastatic potential than basal cell carcinoma.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A rapidly progressive painful unilateral proptosis in a child is most suggestive of:",o:["Cavernous hemangioma","Pleomorphic adenoma","Optic nerve meningioma","Dermoid cyst","Rhabdomyosarcoma"],a:4,e:"Orbital rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common primary malignant orbital tumor of childhood and presents with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis.<br><br>Pain, eyelid edema, and ophthalmoplegia may occur because of aggressive orbital infiltration.<br><br>Cavernous hemangioma (A) usually presents slowly in adults rather than rapidly in children. Dermoid cysts (D) are benign congenital lesions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular tumor is classically associated with Von Hippel-Lindau disease?",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Optic glioma","Sebaceous carcinoma","Retinal capillary hemangioblastoma","Lymphoma"],a:3,e:"Retinal capillary hemangioblastoma is strongly associated with Von Hippel-Lindau disease and may produce exudation or retinal detachment.<br><br>Systemic associations include cerebellar hemangioblastoma and renal cell carcinoma.<br><br>Optic glioma (B) is more strongly associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 rather than Von Hippel-Lindau disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A pigmented conjunctival lesion near the limbus enlarges and develops feeder vessels. Which diagnosis is most concerning?",o:["Pinguecula","Conjunctival nevus","Conjunctival melanoma","Pterygium","Episcleritis"],a:2,e:"Conjunctival melanoma commonly arises from primary acquired melanosis or preexisting nevus and demonstrates enlargement, irregular pigmentation, and feeder vessels.<br><br>Early diagnosis is essential because regional and systemic metastasis may occur.<br><br>Pinguecula (A) is a benign degenerative conjunctival lesion unrelated to malignant melanocytic transformation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which intraocular tumor classically demonstrates a \"mushroom\" configuration on ultrasonography?",o:["Choroidal osteoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Astrocytoma","Hemangioma"],a:2,e:"Choroidal melanoma may produce mushroom or collar-button configuration when the tumor breaks through Bruch membrane.<br><br>Choroidal osteoma (A) appears calcified and plaque-like rather than mushroom-shaped. Retinoblastoma (B) commonly demonstrates calcification.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops bilateral lacrimal gland enlargement with salmon-pink conjunctival lesions. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Orbital cellulitis","Orbital lymphoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Pleomorphic adenoma","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Orbital lymphoma commonly presents with painless progressive proptosis, lacrimal gland enlargement, and characteristic salmon-pink subconjunctival infiltrates.<br><br>Most lesions are extranodal marginal zone B-cell lymphomas.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (A) usually presents acutely with pain, fever, and inflammatory signs rather than chronic painless masses.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with neurofibromatosis type 1 develops slowly progressive unilateral visual loss and proptosis. Which tumor is most likely?",o:["Optic nerve glioma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Sebaceous carcinoma","Hemangioblastoma"],a:0,e:"Optic nerve glioma is strongly associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 and commonly affects children.<br><br>Patients develop slowly progressive visual loss, optic atrophy, and axial proptosis.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (B) usually presents with leukocoria rather than slowly progressive optic nerve enlargement. Choroidal melanoma (C) occurs mainly in adults.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which benign orbital tumor commonly occurs at the frontozygomatic suture in children?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Lymphoma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Optic glioma"],a:0,e:"Dermoid cyst is a congenital choristoma commonly located at the frontozygomatic suture and presents as painless superotemporal orbital swelling in children.<br><br>The lesion is slow-growing and benign.<br><br>Rhabdomyosarcoma (C) presents aggressively with rapid proptosis rather than longstanding painless swelling. Lymphoma (B) is uncommon in children.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which tumor is the most common primary malignant orbital tumor in children?",o:["Lymphoma","Optic glioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Pleomorphic adenoma"],a:2,e:"Rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common primary malignant orbital tumor in children and usually presents with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis.<br><br>Prompt diagnosis and treatment are critical because of aggressive local behavior.<br><br>Optic glioma (B) is generally slower-growing and associated with neurofibromatosis type 1. Cavernous hemangioma (D) is common in adults.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid tumor demonstrates pagetoid spread microscopically?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Keratoacanthoma","Squamous papilloma","Capillary hemangioma","Sebaceous gland carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Sebaceous gland carcinoma may demonstrate pagetoid spread involving conjunctival epithelium, making diagnosis difficult clinically and histologically.<br><br>It is highly malignant and may mimic chronic blepharitis or recurrent chalazion.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) is locally invasive but does not classically exhibit pagetoid intraepithelial spread. Keratoacanthoma (B) is rapidly growing but less aggressive.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A middle-aged woman presents with painless downward displacement of the globe due to lacrimal gland mass. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Metastatic melanoma","Orbital cellulitis","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Pleomorphic adenoma"],a:4,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma is the most common benign epithelial tumor of the lacrimal gland and classically causes painless inferonasal globe displacement.<br><br>Slow progression is typical. Biopsy before complete excision is generally avoided to reduce recurrence risk.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (B) presents acutely with painful inflammatory signs. Rhabdomyosarcoma (C) progresses rapidly in children.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular tumor most commonly metastasizes to the liver?",o:["Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma","Conjunctival papilloma","Hemangioma","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Choroidal melanoma spreads hematogenously, most commonly to the liver because the uveal tract lacks lymphatic drainage.<br><br>Liver metastasis is the major determinant of mortality.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (A) may spread through optic nerve or hematogenously but liver metastasis is classically emphasized with choroidal melanoma.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops rapidly enlarging pigmented lesion of the iris with secondary glaucoma. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Iris melanoma","Iris cyst","Nevus","Pinguecula","Pterygium"],a:0,e:"Iris melanoma may present with enlarging pigmented iris mass, ectropion uveae, secondary glaucoma, and distorted pupil.<br><br>Although prognosis is generally better than posterior uveal melanoma, malignant potential remains significant.<br><br>Iris cysts (B) are often translucent and benign. Pinguecula (D) affects conjunctiva rather than iris tissue.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which conjunctival tumor is strongly associated with human papillomavirus infection?",o:["Squamous papilloma","Melanoma","Lymphoma","Kaposi sarcoma","Sebaceous carcinoma"],a:0,e:"Conjunctival squamous papilloma is a benign epithelial tumor commonly associated with human papillomavirus infection, especially HPV 6 and 11.<br><br>It appears as a pedunculated vascular conjunctival mass.<br><br>Conjunctival melanoma (B) is a malignant melanocytic lesion unrelated primarily to HPV infection. Kaposi sarcoma (D) is linked to HIV-associated HHV-8 infection.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which tumor is most strongly associated with AIDS-related ocular malignancy?",o:["Basal cell carcinoma","Choroidal osteoma","Kaposi sarcoma","Retinoblastoma","Dermoid cyst"],a:2,e:"Kaposi sarcoma is an AIDS-associated vascular malignancy that may involve eyelids and conjunctiva as reddish-purple lesions.<br><br>Human herpesvirus 8 infection plays a major pathogenic role.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (A) is related primarily to ultraviolet exposure rather than immunodeficiency-associated viral oncogenesis.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painless progressive unilateral proptosis and optic disc edema. Imaging shows optic nerve sheath calcification. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Optic nerve glioma","Optic nerve meningioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Orbital pseudotumor"],a:1,e:"Optic nerve meningioma commonly affects middle-aged women and presents with progressive visual loss, proptosis, and optociliary shunt vessels.<br><br>Calcification of the optic nerve sheath on imaging is a classic diagnostic clue.<br><br>Optic nerve glioma (A) more commonly affects children and is associated with neurofibromatosis type 1. Orbital pseudotumor (E) is inflammatory and painful.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with unilateral proptosis and \"cat's eye reflex.\" Fundus examination reveals a white retinal mass with vitreous seeding. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Coats disease","Persistent fetal vasculature","Choroidal melanoma","Retinal detachment","Retinoblastoma"],a:4,e:"Retinoblastoma classically presents with leukocoria, vitreous seeding, and intraocular white retinal tumor in young children.<br><br>Delayed diagnosis may lead to optic nerve invasion and metastatic spread.<br><br>Coats disease (A) may mimic leukocoria but usually demonstrates retinal telangiectasia and exudation without vitreous tumor seeding. Choroidal melanoma (C) mainly affects adults.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A painless pigmented choroidal lesion demonstrates orange pigment and subretinal fluid. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Choroidal nevus","Retinoschisis","Choroidal osteoma","Choroidal melanoma","Astrocytoma"],a:3,e:"Orange lipofuscin pigment and subretinal fluid are important warning signs suggesting malignant choroidal melanoma rather than benign nevus.<br><br>Documented lesion enlargement further supports malignancy.<br><br>Choroidal nevus (A) is generally flat and stable with drusen rather than active subretinal fluid leakage. Choroidal osteoma (C) is calcified and yellow-white.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which eyelid malignancy is most commonly found at the lower eyelid?",o:["Sebaceous gland carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous papilloma","Keratoacanthoma","Capillary hemangioma"],a:1,e:"Basal cell carcinoma most frequently affects the lower eyelid and medial canthus because these regions receive significant chronic ultraviolet exposure.<br><br>The lesion is typically pearly with rolled borders and telangiectasia.<br><br>Sebaceous gland carcinoma (A) more commonly involves the upper eyelid because of meibomian gland abundance. Capillary hemangioma (E) is benign childhood vascular proliferation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A middle-aged patient presents with painless salmon-colored conjunctival patch and mild proptosis. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Orbital cellulitis","Kaposi sarcoma","Episcleritis","Pterygium","Conjunctival lymphoma"],a:4,e:"Conjunctival lymphoma classically presents as painless salmon-pink subconjunctival infiltrates and may be associated with orbital lymphoid disease.<br><br>Most cases are low-grade B-cell lymphomas.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (A) causes acute painful inflammatory symptoms. Episcleritis (C) produces localized vascular congestion rather than infiltrative salmon-colored lesions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which orbital tumor is strongly associated with neurofibromatosis type 1?",o:["Optic nerve glioma","Cavernous hemangioma","Pleomorphic adenoma","Lymphoma","Dermoid cyst"],a:0,e:"Optic nerve glioma commonly occurs in children with neurofibromatosis type 1 and produces progressive proptosis and visual loss.<br><br>The tumor is usually pilocytic astrocytoma histologically.<br><br>Cavernous hemangioma (B) is the most common benign adult orbital tumor but lacks strong NF1 association. Dermoid cyst (E) is congenital and benign.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which tumor is most likely when a child develops rapidly progressive proptosis over days?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Optic glioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Pleomorphic adenoma"],a:2,e:"Rhabdomyosarcoma is a highly aggressive malignant orbital tumor of childhood characterized by rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis.<br><br>Associated eyelid edema and ophthalmoplegia may occur because of rapid orbital infiltration.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) is slow-growing and congenital. Optic glioma (B) generally progresses gradually over months or years.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which ocular tumor demonstrates calcification and arises near the optic disc in young women?",o:["Choroidal melanoma","Choroidal osteoma","Retinoblastoma","Astrocytoma","Hemangioblastoma"],a:1,e:"Choroidal osteoma is a benign ossifying tumor appearing as a yellow-white calcified lesion commonly near the optic disc or macula in young women.<br><br>Visual impairment may occur because of choroidal neovascularization.<br><br>Retinoblastoma (C) demonstrates calcification in children rather than adults. Choroidal melanoma (A) is malignant and usually pigmented.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which tumor is most strongly associated with HIV/AIDS?",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Dermoid cyst","Choroidal nevus","Kaposi sarcoma","Hemangioma"],a:3,e:"Kaposi sarcoma is an AIDS-associated vascular malignancy involving conjunctiva or eyelids as reddish-purple vascular lesions.<br><br>Human herpesvirus 8 is implicated in pathogenesis.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (A) is a benign lacrimal gland epithelial tumor unrelated to immunodeficiency states. Choroidal nevus (C) is benign melanocytic proliferation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with lacrimal gland tumor develops painless inferonasal displacement of the globe. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Orbital cellulitis","Sebaceous carcinoma","Retinoblastoma","Choroidal melanoma"],a:0,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma of the lacrimal gland typically presents with slow painless inferonasal globe displacement because the mass arises in the superotemporal orbit.<br><br>Complete surgical excision is recommended to prevent recurrence.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (B) presents acutely with pain and inflammatory signs. Sebaceous carcinoma (C) primarily involves eyelids rather than lacrimal gland.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which tumor is the most common benign orbital tumor in adults?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Lymphoma","Optic glioma","Cavernous hemangioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma"],a:3,e:"Cavernous hemangioma is the most common benign orbital tumor in adults and typically presents with painless slowly progressive axial proptosis.<br><br>Imaging usually demonstrates a well-circumscribed intraconal vascular lesion.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) is more common in children and usually presents superficially near orbital sutures. Rhabdomyosarcoma (E) is malignant and rapidly progressive.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bitemporal hemianopia undergoes MRI brain. Which lesion is most likely to be identified?",o:["Occipital infarct","Pituitary adenoma","Optic neuritis","Retinal detachment","Orbital cellulitis"],a:1,e:"Bitemporal hemianopia classically results from optic chiasmal compression, most commonly due to pituitary adenoma. MRI brain with sellar views is the preferred investigation.<br><br>Compression damages crossing nasal retinal fibers responsible for temporal visual fields.<br><br>Occipital infarcts (A) typically produce homonymous hemianopia rather than bitemporal defects. Retinal detachment (D) does not produce symmetric chiasmal visual field loss.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is most useful in suspected optic neuritis associated with multiple sclerosis?",o:["CT orbit","X-ray skull","B-scan ultrasonography","OCT cornea","MRI brain and orbit"],a:4,e:"MRI brain and orbit is the investigation of choice in optic neuritis because it demonstrates demyelinating plaques and optic nerve inflammation.<br><br>Presence of white matter lesions predicts future risk of multiple sclerosis.<br><br>CT orbit (A) is inferior for detecting demyelinating lesions. B-scan ultrasonography (C) evaluates intraocular and orbital masses rather than CNS plaques.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging finding is classically associated with optic nerve meningioma?",o:["Mushroom lesion","Tram-track calcification","Cherry-red spot","Snowbanking","Empty sella"],a:1,e:"Optic nerve meningioma classically demonstrates tram-track calcification surrounding the optic nerve on CT or MRI imaging.<br><br>Patients commonly present with progressive visual loss and optic atrophy.<br><br>Mushroom lesion (A) is associated with choroidal melanoma. Snowbanking (D) occurs in intermediate uveitis rather than optic nerve tumors.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with neurofibromatosis type 1 develops progressive proptosis. MRI reveals fusiform enlargement of optic nerve. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Orbital lymphoma","Meningioma","Pituitary adenoma","Cavernous hemangioma","Optic glioma"],a:4,e:"Optic nerve glioma commonly affects children with neurofibromatosis type 1 and demonstrates fusiform enlargement of the optic nerve on MRI.<br><br>Visual loss and axial proptosis are common clinical findings.<br><br>Orbital lymphoma (A) usually affects adults and presents as infiltrative orbital mass. Cavernous hemangioma (D) is well-circumscribed rather than fusiform.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which neuroimaging modality is preferred for detecting orbital fractures with muscle entrapment?",o:["MRI orbit","Fundus fluorescein angiography","OCT macula","CT orbit","B-scan only"],a:3,e:"CT orbit is the preferred imaging modality for orbital fractures because it demonstrates bony details and extraocular muscle entrapment clearly.<br><br>Blowout fractures commonly involve the orbital floor.<br><br>MRI orbit (A) is superior for soft tissue and optic nerve pathology rather than acute bony trauma. OCT macula (C) evaluates retinal layers only.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is most useful in suspected carotid-cavernous fistula?",o:["CT angiography","Keratometry","Tonography","Gonioscopy","Schirmer testing"],a:0,e:"CT angiography and MR angiography are important investigations in carotid-cavernous fistula because they demonstrate abnormal vascular communication and enlarged superior ophthalmic vein.<br><br>Patients often present with pulsatile proptosis and conjunctival congestion.<br><br>Gonioscopy (D) evaluates anterior chamber angle and is unrelated to vascular fistula diagnosis. Schirmer testing (E) assesses tear production.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which neuroimaging finding is typical in idiopathic intracranial hypertension?",o:["Enlarged optic nerve sheath","Choroidal excavation","Retinal tear","Orbital fracture","Calcified lens"],a:0,e:"MRI in idiopathic intracranial hypertension may demonstrate enlarged optic nerve sheath, flattened posterior sclera, and partially empty sella.<br><br>Papilledema is the classic ophthalmic manifestation.<br><br>Retinal tears (C) are unrelated to raised intracranial pressure. Orbital fractures (D) are traumatic abnormalities detected on CT imaging.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most sensitive for detecting demyelinating plaques in multiple sclerosis?",o:["Skull X-ray","B-scan ultrasonography","MRI brain","OCT cornea","CT paranasal sinuses"],a:2,e:"MRI brain is the most sensitive imaging modality for detecting white matter demyelinating plaques in multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Periventricular lesions are commonly identified in patients with optic neuritis.<br><br>Skull X-ray (A) lacks sensitivity for intracranial demyelinating disease. B-scan ultrasonography (B) evaluates ocular and orbital structures only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painful ophthalmoplegia and cavernous sinus involvement on MRI. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Tolosa-Hunt syndrome","Retinal detachment","Optic neuritis","Pituitary adenoma","Chalazion"],a:0,e:"Tolosa-Hunt syndrome is an idiopathic granulomatous inflammation involving the cavernous sinus and presents with painful ophthalmoplegia.<br><br>MRI may show cavernous sinus enhancement or inflammatory tissue.<br><br>Optic neuritis (C) primarily affects optic nerve rather than cranial nerves controlling eye movements. Pituitary adenoma (D) usually causes chiasmal compression.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is best for evaluating optic chiasm compression?",o:["Corneal topography","OCT RNFL","Keratometry","Fundus photography","MRI sellar region"],a:4,e:"MRI of the sellar and parasellar region is the investigation of choice for optic chiasm compression caused by pituitary adenoma or suprasellar masses.<br><br>It provides excellent visualization of optic pathways and surrounding soft tissues.<br><br>OCT RNFL (B) measures retinal nerve fiber thickness but cannot identify sellar masses directly. Keratometry (C) assesses corneal curvature only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging finding strongly suggests orbital cellulitis rather than preseptal cellulitis?",o:["Thickened cornea","Postseptal orbital fat inflammation","Cataract formation","Lens calcification","Retinal hemorrhage"],a:1,e:"Orbital cellulitis demonstrates postseptal inflammatory changes including orbital fat stranding, muscle involvement, or abscess formation on CT imaging.<br><br>This distinction is clinically important because orbital cellulitis threatens vision and life.<br><br>Preseptal cellulitis lacks orbital fat involvement. Cataract formation (C) and retinal hemorrhage (E) are unrelated imaging findings.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which neuroimaging modality is preferred in suspected cavernous sinus thrombosis?",o:["MRI with venography","Keratometry","Pachymetry","Gonioscopy","Electroretinography"],a:0,e:"MRI combined with venography is highly useful for diagnosing cavernous sinus thrombosis because it demonstrates venous occlusion and sinus abnormalities.<br><br>Patients may present with painful ophthalmoplegia, fever, and bilateral orbital signs.<br><br>Electroretinography (E) evaluates retinal electrical function rather than intracranial venous thrombosis. Pachymetry (C) measures corneal thickness only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is preferred for detecting intraocular calcification in retinoblastoma?",o:["MRI orbit","Gonioscopy","OCT macula","Fluorescein angiography","CT scan"],a:4,e:"CT scanning is highly effective for demonstrating intraocular calcification, a hallmark feature of retinoblastoma.<br><br>The modality remains heavily emphasized in pediatric ocular oncology recalls.<br><br>MRI orbit (A) is excellent for soft tissue extension but less sensitive for calcification detection. Gonioscopy (B) evaluates anterior chamber angle only.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which MRI feature is commonly seen in optic neuritis?",o:["Vitreous hemorrhage","Corneal thinning","Lens opacity","Optic nerve enhancement","Retinal dialysis"],a:3,e:"MRI orbit with gadolinium commonly demonstrates optic nerve enhancement in acute optic neuritis because of inflammatory demyelination.<br><br>Associated cerebral plaques may suggest multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Corneal thinning (B) occurs in ectatic corneal disorders rather than optic nerve disease. Retinal dialysis (E) is a peripheral retinal break.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which orbital lesion typically appears as a well-circumscribed intraconal mass on imaging?",o:["Cavernous hemangioma","Orbital cellulitis","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Diffuse lymphoma","Thyroid eye disease"],a:0,e:"Cavernous hemangioma is the most common benign adult orbital tumor and appears as a well-circumscribed intraconal lesion on CT or MRI imaging.<br><br>Patients usually develop painless slowly progressive axial proptosis.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (B) causes diffuse inflammatory changes rather than encapsulated mass lesions. Thyroid eye disease (E) demonstrates extraocular muscle enlargement.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging finding is classic in thyroid eye disease?",o:["Enlargement of extraocular muscles sparing tendons","Retinal detachment","Optic nerve calcification","Choroidal excavation","Empty globe"],a:0,e:"Thyroid eye disease classically produces fusiform enlargement of extraocular muscles with tendon sparing on CT or MRI imaging.<br><br>Inferior rectus is most commonly affected.<br><br>Optic nerve calcification (C) suggests optic nerve meningioma. Retinal detachment (B) is unrelated to thyroid orbitopathy imaging.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is most useful in evaluating choroidal melanoma?",o:["B-scan ultrasonography","Schirmer testing","OCT cornea","Tonography","Visual evoked potential"],a:0,e:"B-scan ultrasonography is highly useful in choroidal melanoma because it demonstrates tumor dimensions, internal reflectivity, and extrascleral extension.<br><br>Mushroom configuration is a classic feature.<br><br>Visual evoked potential (E) evaluates optic nerve conduction rather than intraocular tumors. Tonography (D) assesses aqueous outflow facility.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging sign is associated with carotid-cavernous fistula?",o:["Enlarged superior ophthalmic vein","Cherry-red spot","Corneal hydrops","Optic disc drusen","Macular hole"],a:0,e:"Carotid-cavernous fistula commonly demonstrates enlarged superior ophthalmic vein on CT angiography or MRI because of venous congestion.<br><br>Patients present with pulsatile proptosis and corkscrew conjunctival vessels.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (B) occurs in central retinal artery occlusion. Corneal hydrops (C) is associated with keratoconus.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which neuroimaging modality provides best soft tissue detail for orbital apex lesions?",o:["Pachymetry","Skull X-ray","Keratometry","OCT RNFL","MRI orbit"],a:4,e:"MRI orbit provides superior soft tissue contrast and is the preferred modality for orbital apex lesions affecting optic nerve, muscles, or cavernous sinus structures.<br><br>It is especially useful in inflammatory and neoplastic conditions.<br><br>Skull X-ray (B) has poor soft tissue resolution. OCT RNFL (D) evaluates retinal nerve fiber layer rather than orbital apex anatomy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with papilledema undergoes MRI that reveals partially empty sella and enlarged optic nerve sheath. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Retinal detachment","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Orbital cellulitis","Optic glioma","Choroidal melanoma"],a:1,e:"Idiopathic intracranial hypertension commonly demonstrates partially empty sella, enlarged optic nerve sheath, and posterior scleral flattening on MRI.<br><br>Papilledema is the hallmark ophthalmic finding.<br><br>Optic glioma (D) produces fusiform optic nerve enlargement rather than diffuse raised intracranial pressure signs. Choroidal melanoma (E) is an intraocular tumor.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 32-year-old obese woman presents with transient visual obscurations, pulsatile tinnitus, and bilateral papilledema. MRI brain is normal except for partially empty sella and enlarged perioptic CSF spaces. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Optic neuritis","Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Pituitary apoplexy","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Foster Kennedy syndrome"],a:1,e:"Idiopathic intracranial hypertension classically affects obese women of childbearing age and presents with headache, transient visual obscurations, papilledema, and pulsatile tinnitus.<br><br>MRI findings include partially empty sella and enlarged optic nerve sheath spaces.<br><br>Optic neuritis (A) usually causes painful unilateral visual loss with RAPD rather than bilateral papilledema. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (D) produces painful ophthalmoplegia and systemic illness.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive unilateral proptosis undergoes CT orbit showing enlargement of extraocular muscles sparing tendons. Which muscle is most commonly affected first in thyroid eye disease?",o:["Superior oblique","Inferior rectus","Lateral rectus","Superior rectus","Medial rectus"],a:1,e:"Thyroid eye disease classically demonstrates fusiform enlargement of extraocular muscles with tendon sparing on orbital imaging. Inferior rectus involvement is most common initially.<br><br>Patients often develop restrictive hypotropia and vertical diplopia.<br><br>Superior oblique (A) involvement is uncommon because the disease preferentially affects rectus muscles. Lateral rectus (C) is less frequently affected early.<br><br><em>(Recall and Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops painful ophthalmoplegia, decreased corneal sensation, and cavernous sinus enhancement on MRI. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Tolosa-Hunt syndrome","Orbital cellulitis","Optic neuritis","Retinoblastoma","Pituitary adenoma"],a:0,e:"Tolosa-Hunt syndrome is an idiopathic granulomatous inflammation involving the cavernous sinus and superior orbital fissure, causing painful ophthalmoplegia.<br><br>MRI commonly demonstrates cavernous sinus enhancement or inflammatory soft tissue.<br><br>Orbital cellulitis (B) usually presents with fever and diffuse orbital inflammation rather than isolated cavernous sinus granulomatous enhancement. Pituitary adenoma (E) primarily compresses optic chiasm.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 12-year-old child with neurofibromatosis type 1 presents with slowly progressive visual loss. MRI demonstrates fusiform enlargement of the optic nerve without calcification. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Optic nerve meningioma","Optic nerve glioma","Cavernous hemangioma","Orbital lymphoma","Dermoid cyst"],a:1,e:"Optic nerve glioma is strongly associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 and typically presents in childhood with slowly progressive visual loss and proptosis.<br><br>MRI shows fusiform enlargement of the optic nerve.<br><br>Optic nerve meningioma (A) more commonly affects middle-aged women and often demonstrates tram-track calcification. Orbital lymphoma (D) rarely presents in childhood.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bitemporal hemianopia undergoes MRI showing suprasellar mass compressing the optic chiasm from below. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Craniopharyngioma","Retinal detachment","Orbital pseudotumor","Choroidal melanoma","Central retinal artery occlusion"],a:0,e:"Craniopharyngioma is a suprasellar tumor that commonly compresses the optic chiasm and produces bitemporal hemianopia, especially in children and young adults.<br><br>Calcification is a classic radiological feature.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) produces monocular visual disturbance rather than chiasmal field defects. Choroidal melanoma (D) is an intraocular tumor without suprasellar extension.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe facial trauma develops diplopia on upward gaze. CT orbit demonstrates orbital floor fracture with inferior rectus entrapment. Which type of fracture is most likely?",o:["Le Fort I fracture","Blowout fracture","Zygomatic arch fracture","Nasal bone fracture","Frontal sinus fracture"],a:1,e:"Blowout fracture classically involves the orbital floor and may entrap inferior rectus muscle, producing vertical diplopia and limitation of upward gaze.<br><br>CT orbit is the preferred investigation for diagnosis.<br><br>Le Fort I fracture (A) involves maxilla rather than isolated orbital floor entrapment. Nasal bone fracture (D) does not typically cause extraocular muscle incarceration.<br><br><em>(Recall and Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with pulsatile proptosis, corkscrew conjunctival vessels, and bruit over the eye. CT angiography shows dilated superior ophthalmic vein. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Thyroid eye disease","Carotid-cavernous fistula","Orbital cellulitis","Cavernous hemangioma","Optic neuritis"],a:1,e:"Carotid-cavernous fistula causes abnormal arteriovenous communication within the cavernous sinus leading to venous congestion and pulsatile proptosis.<br><br>Dilated superior ophthalmic vein on CT angiography is a classic imaging feature.<br><br>Thyroid eye disease (A) produces muscle enlargement without pulsatile bruit. Cavernous hemangioma (D) is a slow-growing benign orbital mass.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with headache and papilledema undergoes MRI showing ring-enhancing lesion with surrounding edema in occipital lobe. Which condition should be strongly considered?",o:["Choroidal nevus","Optic neuritis","Pituitary adenoma","Brain abscess","Keratoconus"],a:3,e:"Ring-enhancing lesion with surrounding edema on MRI strongly suggests brain abscess, especially when associated with raised intracranial pressure and papilledema.<br><br>Neuro-ophthalmic manifestations occur because of intracranial mass effect.<br><br>Optic neuritis (B) causes optic nerve enhancement rather than intracerebral ring lesions. Pituitary adenoma (C) usually affects the sellar region instead of occipital lobe.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral optic atrophy and contralateral papilledema undergoes MRI brain. Which lesion is most likely responsible?",o:["Frontal lobe mass","Retinal detachment","Orbital cellulitis","Choroidal melanoma","Cataract"],a:0,e:"Foster Kennedy syndrome consists of ipsilateral optic atrophy and contralateral papilledema caused by frontal lobe tumors compressing one optic nerve while increasing intracranial pressure.<br><br>MRI brain is essential for diagnosis.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) and cataract (E) do not produce this characteristic neuro-ophthalmic combination. Orbital cellulitis (C) presents with inflammatory orbital signs.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic headache develops homonymous hemianopia. MRI demonstrates occipital lobe infarction. Which vascular territory is most likely involved?",o:["Middle cerebral artery","Basilar perforators only","Anterior cerebral artery","Ophthalmic artery","Posterior cerebral artery"],a:4,e:"Occipital lobe infarction involving the posterior cerebral artery territory classically produces contralateral homonymous hemianopia.<br><br>Macular sparing may occur because of dual vascular supply from middle cerebral artery branches.<br><br>Middle cerebral artery infarction (A) more commonly affects frontal and parietal lobes. Ophthalmic artery occlusion (D) produces retinal ischemia rather than cortical visual field defects.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic patient presents with complete ptosis, \"down and out\" eye position, but normal pupillary reactions. Which cranial nerve palsy is most likely?",o:["Fourth nerve palsy","Sixth nerve palsy","Pupil-sparing third nerve palsy","Horner syndrome","Optic neuritis"],a:2,e:"Microvascular ischemia in diabetes commonly causes pupil-sparing third cranial nerve palsy because central motor fibers are affected while superficial parasympathetic pupillary fibers remain intact.<br><br>Patients develop ptosis and ophthalmoplegia with preserved pupillary reflexes.<br><br>Fourth nerve palsy (A) primarily causes vertical diplopia. Horner syndrome (D) presents with ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis rather than \"down and out\" deviation.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient complains of vertical diplopia worsening while descending stairs and reading. Which cranial nerve is most likely involved?",o:["Oculomotor nerve","Optic nerve","Abducens nerve","Trochlear nerve","Facial nerve"],a:3,e:"Trochlear nerve palsy causes superior oblique weakness leading to vertical diplopia that worsens during downgaze activities such as reading or descending stairs.<br><br>Patients often compensate with contralateral head tilt.<br><br>Abducens palsy (C) causes horizontal diplopia due to impaired abduction. Optic nerve lesions (B) impair vision without causing ocular misalignment.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A young woman presents with painful visual loss, red desaturation, and pain on eye movement. MRI demonstrates demyelinating plaques. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Papilledema","Optic neuritis","Retinal detachment","Central retinal artery occlusion","Pituitary adenoma"],a:1,e:"Optic neuritis commonly presents with painful monocular visual loss, dyschromatopsia, and pain aggravated by eye movement.<br><br>MRI brain frequently reveals demyelinating plaques suggestive of multiple sclerosis.<br><br>Papilledema (A) usually preserves visual acuity initially and is bilateral. Central retinal artery occlusion (D) causes sudden painless visual loss with cherry-red spot.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which neuroimaging finding is classically associated with optic nerve meningioma?",o:["Enlarged superior ophthalmic vein","Macular edema","Mushroom lesion","Empty sella","Tram-track calcification"],a:4,e:"Optic nerve meningioma classically demonstrates tram-track calcification surrounding the optic nerve on CT or MRI imaging.<br><br>Patients usually develop progressive visual loss and optic atrophy.<br><br>Mushroom lesion (C) is associated with choroidal melanoma. Enlarged superior ophthalmic vein (A) suggests carotid-cavernous fistula.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with bilateral papilledema and transient visual obscurations. Vision is initially preserved. Which statement regarding papilledema is most accurate?",o:["It is usually unilateral","It occurs due to raised intracranial pressure","Early severe blindness is universal","It is caused by retinal detachment","RAPD is always present"],a:1,e:"Papilledema refers to bilateral optic disc swelling caused by raised intracranial pressure transmitted through the optic nerve sheath.<br><br>Visual acuity is often preserved initially despite enlarged blind spots.<br><br>Retinal detachment (D) causes monocular visual field defects rather than bilateral disc edema. RAPD (E) is not usually present in symmetric papilledema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with horizontal diplopia cannot abduct the right eye. Which cranial nerve palsy is present?",o:["Right third nerve palsy","Left sixth nerve palsy","Right sixth nerve palsy","Right fourth nerve palsy","Left third nerve palsy"],a:2,e:"Abducens nerve palsy causes weakness of lateral rectus muscle leading to defective abduction and horizontal diplopia.<br><br>Raised intracranial pressure is an important cause because the sixth nerve has a long intracranial course.<br><br>Fourth nerve palsy (D) causes vertical diplopia instead of isolated abduction failure. Third nerve palsy (A) produces ptosis and multidirectional movement deficits.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"MRI brain of a patient with bitemporal hemianopia demonstrates a sellar mass compressing the optic chiasm. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Pituitary adenoma","Optic neuritis","Occipital infarct","Retinoblastoma","Cavernous hemangioma"],a:0,e:"Pituitary adenoma is the most common sellar lesion causing optic chiasmal compression and bitemporal hemianopia.<br><br>MRI sellar imaging is the preferred neuroimaging investigation.<br><br>Occipital infarct (C) causes homonymous hemianopia rather than bitemporal field defects. Optic neuritis (B) produces central scotoma and painful vision loss.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with pulsatile proptosis, bruit, and corkscrew conjunctival vessels. CT angiography shows dilated superior ophthalmic vein. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Orbital cellulitis","Cavernous hemangioma","Carotid-cavernous fistula","Thyroid eye disease","Optic glioma"],a:2,e:"Carotid-cavernous fistula produces abnormal communication between carotid circulation and cavernous sinus, resulting in venous congestion and pulsatile proptosis.<br><br>Dilated superior ophthalmic vein is a classic imaging feature.<br><br>Thyroid eye disease (D) causes extraocular muscle enlargement without bruit or arterialized conjunctival vessels. Optic glioma (E) usually presents in childhood.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"Which visual field defect is classically associated with optic neuritis?",o:["Homonymous hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Central scotoma","Binasal hemianopia","Altitudinal defect only"],a:2,e:"Central scotoma occurs in optic neuritis because papillomacular fibers are preferentially affected by inflammatory demyelination.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of blurred central vision and impaired color perception.<br><br>Homonymous hemianopia (A) indicates retrochiasmal lesions. Altitudinal defects (E) are more typical of ischemic optic neuropathy.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with frontal lobe tumor develops ipsilateral optic atrophy and contralateral papilledema. This syndrome is called:",o:["Horner syndrome","Tolosa-Hunt syndrome","Parinaud syndrome","Foster Kennedy syndrome","Adie syndrome"],a:3,e:"Foster Kennedy syndrome results from frontal lobe mass causing direct optic nerve compression on one side with raised intracranial pressure producing contralateral papilledema.<br><br>MRI brain is essential for confirming the intracranial lesion.<br><br>Parinaud syndrome (C) causes vertical gaze palsy. Horner syndrome (A) produces ptosis and miosis rather than papilledema.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient tilts his head to compensate for vertical diplopia caused by superior oblique weakness. Which cranial nerve is involved?",o:["Third nerve","Optic nerve","Sixth nerve","Seventh nerve","Fourth nerve"],a:4,e:"Trochlear nerve palsy weakens the superior oblique muscle and causes vertical diplopia with compensatory contralateral head tilt.<br><br>Symptoms worsen during downgaze activities.<br><br>Sixth nerve palsy (C) causes horizontal diplopia due to impaired lateral rectus function. Optic nerve lesions (B) do not cause ocular motility imbalance.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which imaging modality is most sensitive for detecting demyelinating plaques in multiple sclerosis?",o:["Skull X-ray","CT orbit","MRI brain","B-scan ultrasonography","OCT cornea"],a:2,e:"MRI brain is the most sensitive modality for detecting periventricular demyelinating plaques in multiple sclerosis.<br><br>It plays a crucial role in evaluating optic neuritis patients.<br><br>CT orbit (B) is inferior for white matter lesion detection. B-scan ultrasonography (D) evaluates ocular and orbital masses rather than CNS demyelination.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with papilledema but preserved visual acuity initially. Which visual field defect is most characteristic early in disease?",o:["Central scotoma","Enlarged blind spot","Bitemporal hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Altitudinal defect"],a:1,e:"Early papilledema commonly produces enlarged blind spot because optic disc swelling affects the peripapillary retina.<br><br>Visual acuity often remains normal during initial stages.<br><br>Central scotoma (A) is more characteristic of optic neuritis. Bitemporal hemianopia (C) indicates optic chiasm compression.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"MRI orbit demonstrates fusiform enlargement of optic nerve in a child with neurofibromatosis type 1. Which tumor is most likely?",o:["Optic nerve glioma","Meningioma","Lymphoma","Pituitary adenoma","Choroidal melanoma"],a:0,e:"Optic nerve glioma is strongly associated with neurofibromatosis type 1 and appears as fusiform optic nerve enlargement on MRI.<br><br>Children present with progressive visual loss and proptosis.<br><br>Meningioma (B) more commonly affects adults and demonstrates tram-track calcification. Choroidal melanoma (E) is an intraocular tumor of adulthood.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful ophthalmoplegia and cavernous sinus enhancement on MRI most likely has:",o:["Tolosa-Hunt syndrome","Retinal detachment","Optic neuritis","Cataract","Macular degeneration"],a:0,e:"Tolosa-Hunt syndrome is granulomatous inflammation involving the cavernous sinus and superior orbital fissure producing painful ophthalmoplegia.<br><br>MRI may reveal cavernous sinus enhancement.<br><br>Retinal detachment (B) causes flashes and floaters without cranial nerve palsies. Cataract (D) does not produce painful ophthalmoplegia.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which cranial nerve palsy is commonly considered a false localizing sign in raised intracranial pressure?",o:["Third nerve palsy","Fourth nerve palsy","Sixth nerve palsy","Facial nerve palsy","Optic nerve palsy"],a:2,e:"Sixth cranial nerve palsy is a classic false localizing sign in raised intracranial pressure because the nerve has a long intracranial course vulnerable to stretching.<br><br>Patients develop horizontal diplopia due to lateral rectus weakness.<br><br>Third nerve palsy (A) more commonly indicates compressive aneurysm. Fourth nerve palsy (B) causes vertical diplopia rather than false localization.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops painful monocular visual loss with RAPD and normal optic disc appearance. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Papilledema","Macular hole","Retinal vein occlusion","Papillitis","Retrobulbar neuritis"],a:4,e:"Retrobulbar neuritis involves posterior optic nerve inflammation, producing painful visual loss and RAPD despite initially normal optic disc appearance.<br><br>The classic teaching is that the patient sees nothing while the doctor sees nothing.<br><br>Papillitis (D) causes visible optic disc edema. Papilledema (A) is usually bilateral and related to raised intracranial pressure.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which tumor most commonly causes chiasmal compression with bitemporal hemianopia in adults?",o:["Craniopharyngioma","Optic glioma","Retinoblastoma","Pituitary adenoma","Orbital lymphoma"],a:3,e:"Pituitary adenoma is the most common adult lesion causing optic chiasm compression and bitemporal hemianopia.<br><br>MRI sellar imaging confirms diagnosis and extent of compression.<br><br>Craniopharyngioma (A) is more common in children and young adults. Retinoblastoma (C) is an intraocular childhood tumor.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with papilledema develops secondary optic atrophy if untreated. Which fundoscopic feature suggests chronic disease?",o:["Hyperemic swollen disc","Pale elevated disc","Cherry-red spot","Macular star","Vitreous hemorrhage"],a:1,e:"Chronic papilledema eventually produces secondary optic atrophy characterized by pale swollen optic discs and progressive visual impairment.<br><br>Persistent raised intracranial pressure damages optic nerve fibers irreversibly.<br><br>Cherry-red spot (C) occurs in retinal arterial occlusion. Macular star (D) is characteristic of neuroretinitis rather than chronic papilledema.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which statement regarding optic neuritis is most accurate?",o:["Pain on eye movement is uncommon","Visual recovery is usually poor","Multiple sclerosis association is strong","It usually presents with bilateral papilledema","RAPD is absent"],a:2,e:"Optic neuritis is strongly associated with multiple sclerosis, especially in young females presenting with painful monocular visual loss.<br><br>MRI brain lesions increase future MS risk substantially.<br><br>Pain on eye movement (A) is common and highly characteristic. RAPD (E) is usually present in unilateral disease.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe headache develops bilateral papilledema and sixth nerve palsy. MRI brain is normal, but MR venography shows venous sinus obstruction. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Cavernous sinus thrombosis","Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis","Optic neuritis","Pituitary adenoma"],a:2,e:"Cerebral venous sinus thrombosis causes raised intracranial pressure leading to papilledema, headache, and sixth nerve palsy. MR venography is highly useful for diagnosis.<br><br>Young females with hypercoagulable states are commonly affected.<br><br>Idiopathic intracranial hypertension (A) usually demonstrates normal venous drainage. Cavernous sinus thrombosis (B) presents with painful ophthalmoplegia and orbital congestion.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute painful visual loss has delayed P100 latency on visual evoked potential testing. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Retinal detachment","Pituitary adenoma","Papilledema","Central retinal vein occlusion","Optic neuritis"],a:4,e:"Visual evoked potential demonstrates delayed P100 latency in optic neuritis because demyelination slows optic nerve conduction.<br><br>This investigation may detect subclinical demyelinating disease even after visual recovery.<br><br>Papilledema (C) initially preserves conduction and visual acuity. Retinal detachment (A) affects retina rather than optic nerve pathways.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with unilateral ptosis, mydriasis, and \"down and out\" eye position. Which cause must urgently be excluded by neuroimaging?",o:["Microvascular diabetes","Posterior communicating artery aneurysm","Thyroid eye disease","Orbital cellulitis","Optic neuritis"],a:1,e:"Painful third nerve palsy with pupillary involvement strongly suggests compressive aneurysm, particularly posterior communicating artery aneurysm.<br><br>Urgent neuroimaging with angiography is essential because rupture may be fatal.<br><br>Microvascular diabetic palsy (A) usually spares the pupil. Thyroid eye disease (C) causes restrictive ophthalmopathy rather than isolated cranial nerve palsy.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops bilateral progressive visual loss and optic atrophy. MRI demonstrates enlarged pituitary mass compressing the optic chiasm superiorly. Which visual field defect is expected?",o:["Homonymous hemianopia","Binasal hemianopia","Central scotoma","Bitemporal hemianopia","Enlarged blind spot"],a:3,e:"Pituitary macroadenoma compresses decussating nasal retinal fibers at the optic chiasm, producing bitemporal hemianopia.<br><br>Peripheral temporal fields are affected first.<br><br>Homonymous hemianopia (A) indicates retrochiasmal lesions. Enlarged blind spot (E) is commonly associated with papilledema rather than chiasmal compression.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with papilledema, headache, vomiting, and MRI showing ring-enhancing lesion with surrounding edema. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Brain abscess","Optic neuritis","Choroidal melanoma","Keratoconus","Retinitis pigmentosa"],a:0,e:"Brain abscess produces intracranial mass effect leading to headache, vomiting, papilledema, and focal neurological deficits.<br><br>MRI typically demonstrates ring-enhancing lesion with surrounding vasogenic edema.<br><br>Optic neuritis (B) causes optic nerve enhancement rather than intracerebral ring lesions. Choroidal melanoma (C) is an intraocular tumor.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"Which cranial nerve palsy commonly causes horizontal diplopia that worsens on gaze toward the affected side?",o:["Third nerve palsy","Fourth nerve palsy","Sixth nerve palsy","Facial nerve palsy","Optic nerve lesion"],a:2,e:"Abducens nerve palsy weakens lateral rectus muscle, producing horizontal diplopia maximal on gaze toward the affected side.<br><br>Raised intracranial pressure is an important etiology due to the nerve's long intracranial course.<br><br>Fourth nerve palsy (B) produces vertical diplopia. Optic nerve lesions (E) impair vision but do not cause ocular misalignment.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"MRI orbit of a middle-aged woman shows optic nerve sheath enhancement with tram-track appearance. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Optic neuritis","Optic nerve glioma","Optic nerve meningioma","Cavernous hemangioma","Orbital cellulitis"],a:2,e:"Optic nerve meningioma classically affects middle-aged women and demonstrates tram-track enhancement or calcification surrounding the optic nerve.<br><br>Patients present with slowly progressive visual loss and optic atrophy.<br><br>Optic neuritis (A) causes intrinsic optic nerve enhancement rather than sheath-based tram-track appearance. Optic glioma (B) usually affects children.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with papilledema initially develops which visual field abnormality most commonly?",o:["Central scotoma","Enlarged blind spot","Homonymous hemianopia","Ring scotoma","Bitemporal hemianopia"],a:1,e:"Papilledema enlarges the physiological blind spot because swollen optic discs elevate surrounding peripapillary retina.<br><br>Visual acuity often remains normal in early stages despite marked disc edema.<br><br>Central scotoma (A) is more characteristic of optic neuritis. Homonymous hemianopia (C) indicates retrochiasmal neurological lesions.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis undergoes MRI showing destructive orbital soft tissue mass. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Dermoid cyst","Cavernous hemangioma","Rhabdomyosarcoma","Pleomorphic adenoma","Optic neuritis"],a:2,e:"Rhabdomyosarcoma is the most common primary malignant orbital tumor of childhood and presents with rapidly progressive unilateral proptosis.<br><br>MRI reveals aggressive infiltrative orbital soft tissue mass.<br><br>Dermoid cyst (A) is congenital and slow-growing. Cavernous hemangioma (B) usually presents as benign well-circumscribed adult orbital lesion.<br><br><em>(Parson's Diseases of the Eye)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with painful ophthalmoplegia demonstrates cavernous sinus inflammation on MRI and dramatic steroid response. Which diagnosis is most likely?",o:["Tolosa-Hunt syndrome","Orbital cellulitis","Pituitary adenoma","Thyroid eye disease","Optic glioma"],a:0,e:"Tolosa-Hunt syndrome is granulomatous inflammation involving the cavernous sinus and superior orbital fissure producing painful ophthalmoplegia.<br><br>MRI may show cavernous sinus inflammatory enhancement, and corticosteroid response is typically dramatic.<br><br>Thyroid eye disease (D) causes restrictive myopathy without acute painful cavernous sinus inflammation. Pituitary adenoma (C) usually produces chiasmal symptoms.<br><br><em>(Kanski's Clinical Ophthalmology)</em>"},
];